Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> authorized the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> to resume publishing Wednesday following a 15-day suspension imposed for reporting violence at an anti-government protest. But a statement released Tuesday by the ministry said <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>'s directors at a meeting with government officials `` were admonished for constant disrespect for the laws of the nation.'' Also Tuesday, the ministry suspended for 48 hours the radio news program <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguense </ORGANIZATION>. It accused the program directors of broadcasting `` false news'' but did not elaborate. The program is broadcast by the privately owned station <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mundial </ORGANIZATION>. The left-wing Sandinista government ordered the suspension of <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> on July 12, one day after the newspaper reported a violent police crackdown at a July 10 demonstration in the southern city of <LOCATION> Nandaime </LOCATION>. More than three dozen opposition leaders were detained by police during the demonstration. In ordering the shutdown, the government accused <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> of `` flagrant abuse of the freedom of expression to the detriment of the public order and the interests of the people.'' Also on July 12 the government ordered an indefinite suspension of <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catolica </ORGANIZATION>, the station operated by the Nicaraguan Roman Catholic church, for its reporting of the Nandaime demonstration. <PERSON> Cristiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrios </PERSON>, deputy director of <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday night the newspaper rejected the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s claims it had violated laws. She said Wednesday's editions would include a special section covering events that occurred during the suspension.
