<HEAD>Report Fewer Killed on First Day of Reduced Speed Limits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lower speed limits helped reduce the number of highway fatalities on the first day new summer regulations went into effect, according to police. They said 19 people perished in highway accidents Sunday compared to 25 deaths on the corresponding day last year. The regulations went into effect Sunday and reduced speed limits from 87 mph to 68 mph on major highways and from 68 mph to 56 on secondary roads. Public Works Minister <PERSON> Enrico </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferri </PERSON> anounced the lower limits last week following a weekend in which 95 people were killed in highway accidents. The limits are to be in force until Sept. 11. Police said 6,000 speeding tickets were issued Sunday.
