<FIRST>r w PM-Navy-Blacks Bjt   07-26 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy-Blacks, Bjt,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Promotion of Blacks Lags in Navy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is studying why the promotion of blacks in its ranks lags behind that of the other services, 40 years after President <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> ordered the nation's military to integrate. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has launched an intensive two-month study to report to Chief of Naval Operations Adm. <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON> <PERSON> Trost </PERSON> on why the service has so few black officers and why so many blacks are subject to disciplinary action. The study was initiated at the suggestion of Vice Admiral <PERSON> L.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edney </PERSON>, chief of naval personnel. `` Progress has slowed. We need to find out why,'' <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> said at a convention of the mostly black Naval Officers' Association earlier this month in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The review coincides with the 40th anniversary today of <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>'s Executive Order 9981 for `` equality of treatment and opportunity for all persons in the armed forces without regard to race, color, religion or national origin. The road has been slow, especially in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The number of black officers in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has grown from 254 in 1965 to 2,518 today. But that means that only 3.4 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s officers are black, far behind the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s rate of 10.3 percent, and the 6.6 percent in the military as a whole. In the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, 5.4 percent of the officers are black, and in the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, 5.4 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> goal is to reach 6 percent by 1996. That would be quite a change for a service which declared as recently as 1933 that blacks would be accepted only as mess stewards and which did not name its first black admiral, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gravely </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, until 1971, according to the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> rolls now list six black admirals, two of them promoted this year. The highest ranking black in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is two-star Rear Adm. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hacker </PERSON>, commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> base and naval training center at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, a major port for the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> fleet. `` While we have experienced significant growth in numbers and opportunities for minority personnel, we have clearly not met all of our challenges,'' <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> said in his speech, given July 8. `` Despite our best efforts, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> still suffers from shortages in minority officer accessions, officer promotions, enlisted advancement and _ while lower than past years _ slightly higher minority involvement with uniform code of military justice violations,' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has ordered a separate report, due by the end of the year, to determine why the court-martial rate for blacks last year was 1.65 percent compared to 1.34 percent for all naval personnel. Within two months, a task force is to report to <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Trost </PERSON> on ways to improve the promotion of blacks in the service. <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> proclaimed a commitment to `` keep equal opportunity on the front burner as a top priority. It is the right thing to do. Equal opportunity is fundamental to good leadership, morale and discipline.'' The white majority of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officers, he said, have `` a natural tendency to be less sensitive to the perceptions and human needs of minorities, be they minorities of race, religion or gender.'' `` Top leaders must recognize this tendency and not tolerate such insensitivity. We must have checks and balances to make sure the chain of command is responsive,'' <PERSON> Edney </PERSON> said. The admiral promised that `` this will not be just another study of equal opportunity programs. It will be a hard, introspective look.''
</TEXT>
