<HEAD>Political Debate Over Free Trade Has Parallel In 1911 Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the second time this century, political furor over free trade with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could force a <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> government out of office. The precedent was set in 1911 when long-serving Liberal Prime Minister Sir <PERSON> Wilfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurier </PERSON> proposed free trade but was pressured into an early election and defeated by the Conservatives. The roles are reversed this time. A Conservative prime minister, <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, has negotiated the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, while the Liberal opposition claims the deal will turn <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> into little more than a resource base for the Americans. The agreement to dismantle duties and non-tariff barriers over a 10-year period is scheduled to take effect Jan. 1. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presented final legislation Monday to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> is expected to approve the deal in August. In a bid to halt the ratification process, <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> played his final card last week. The Commons member asked the Liberal-dominated <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, an appointed chamber that can delay and amend legislation, not to consider the bill until <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> calls an election on the issue. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> accused Turner of hijacking the authority of elected members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> _ meaning the Commons where Conservatives hold 207 of the 282 seats. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s argument is that <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> has no mandate for entering a treaty that radically changes the future of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. In 1983, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> spoke against free trade and the issue was not part of the Conservative election platform in 1984. `` The agreement should not go into effect until the people of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> have had the opportunity to vote -LRB- on it -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, who maintains that such a pact would make <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> subservient to its giant neighbor. He urged <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> to call a September election, one year before his five-year term expires. That would provide enough time to implement the agreement if voters return <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> to office. The Liberals would tear up the deal if they win, <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. Polls show Canadians divided 50-50 on the issue and in favor of an election. But <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> reacted calmly to what he termed <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s `` act of desperation'' and said he has a full legislative agenda to complete before an election. He got a political boost Monday when a prominent Liberal, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Roggen </PERSON>, resigned as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> so he could speak out in favor of free trade. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s camp hoped more Liberals would break ranks. `` There's a lot bubbling around here and we'll have to wait and see what kind of stew comes out of the pot,'' <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, a top <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> aide, said. `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> has put a helluva lot of pressure on a lot of senators.'' <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s second opposition party, the socialist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, dislikes free trade. But party leader <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> has accused Turner of abandoning democracy by using the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to impede the will of the elected <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. The Conservatives have climbed steadily in the polls this year, while the other two parties have slumped. For <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, deploying the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is a gamble because he gave the Conservatives two diversionary election issues: his judgment in defying elected legislators and the need for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> reform. `` The election outcome may very well be determined more by people's feelings about the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> than about free trade,'' columnist <ORGANIZATION> Orland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> wrote Monday in The Globe and Mail, the national newspaper. The situation has many parallels with 1911. The Conservatives then stirred up public opinion with the slogan `` No truck nor trade with the <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION>'' and filibustered for five months to force <PERSON> Laurier </PERSON> into an early election. Then, as now, the government had not included free trade in its election platform. But in 1911, the Conservatives did not use the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to stop the treaty.
