<HEAD>Mercedes Sudden Accleration Probe Expanded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 300,000 <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> automobiles are under investigation to determine if hundreds of reports of unintended acceleration are true, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> says. The agency said Monday it had broadened its probe into allegations that the vehicles speed up without the operator's intervention to encompass 309,000 cars made by Mercedes from 1984 through 1988 The cars are all equipped with gasoline engines and automatic transmissions. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> in October had begun an investigation into 42,353 1986-1987 Mercedes Model 124 300E cars. The new engineering analysis broadens the regulatory case to include the Mercedes models 107 SL, 126 SE, SEL and <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, and 201 190E. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> said it has received reports of 301 instances of sudden acceleration in the Mercedes cars. The agency said 217 of the instances reportedly resulted in accidents that injured 92 people and killed one person. <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will cooperate fully with the <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> investigation, said A.B. <PERSON> Schuman </PERSON>, a spokesman for the company in <LOCATION> Montvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. He said in the company's investigation of 283 sudden-acceleration reports, `` our technicians have never found any electrical, electronic or mechanical defect in our cars that could cause unintended acceleration.'' The Mercedes case is among six <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> investigations into alleged sudden acceleration involving at least 4.8 million vehicles. Other makers and the number of vehicles involved are <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 3.2 million; <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 800,000; <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>, 255,000; <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>, 183,000; and <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, 62,500. The Mercedes investigation was opened at the request of the Center for Auto Safety, a consumer group often at odds with the auto industry and its regulators. `` The steady increase in sudden acceleration incidents in numerous Mercedes models other than the 1986-87 300E demonstrates that Mercedes' entire line of recent-year gasoline engine cars with automatic transmissions is affected by this defect,'' the center said. The center said it had received 164 reports of sudden acceleration in Mercedes cars, resulting in 125 accidents, 46 injuries and one death.
