<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's hens worked a little harder last month, but because of fewer birds the extra effort fell short of the year-ago production mark, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. June output was estimated at 5.52 billion eggs, down 2 percent from June 1987, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Meanwhile, the number of hens in laying flocks declined 3 percent during the month to an average of 269 million birds. Individually, however, the fewer hens shelled out more eggs _ an average of 2,054 eggs per 100 birds during June, up from 2,033 a year earlier, the report said.
