<SECOND>AM-Insulation Danger,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Investigating Wiring Insulation at Nuclear Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is re-evaluating the use of a wiring insulation found in most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear power plants after discovering damaged electrical circuits at several facilities, according to a published report. <PERSON> Uldis </PERSON> <PERSON> Potapovs </PERSON>, chief of the commission's unit that inspects vendor-supplied plant equipment, said the insulating material known as <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> appears to damage easily under mechanical stress and even in routine handling by plant maintenance crews, the <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star-Telegram </ORGANIZATION> reported in Tuesday's editions. Worn or damaged <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> has been discovered on electrical wires that connect reactor containment buildings with main-plant control circuits located outside the reactor, <PERSON> Potapovs </PERSON> told the newspaper. He said such damage is a `` significant concern'' because it could cause erroneous equipment readings or failure of equipment, but there has never been a failure serious enough to produce a fire. <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> can be found on wiring in most of the nation's 104 operating nuclear power plants, <PERSON> Potapovs </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON>, made by E.I. du <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemours </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is a thin, lightweight insulation often used to wrap wiring in high-performance aircraft. It has been cited as a factor in dozens of aircraft fires and is suspected of contributing to dozens more, the Star-Telegram has reported in a series of stories this week. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> has long maintained that its insulation does not crack or break any sooner than other insulation. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, which has banned <LOCATION> Kapton </LOCATION> in its aircraft, says the material deteriorates prematurely, cracks easily and even explodes under certain conditions. But other <LOCATION> Kapton </LOCATION> users, including the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and most commercial aircraft builders, say the insulation is the best on the market for the job. Asked if the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> might call for a ban on <LOCATION> Kapton </LOCATION> in nuclear plants, <PERSON> Potapovs </PERSON> said, `` That certainly would be a possibility.'' But <PERSON> Potapovs </PERSON> added that it seems more likely that the agency will issue a non-binding notice to plant operators recommending that <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> wires be reinforced with a sleeve or coating and that maintenance crews be instructed in how to best handle the material. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> has already issued one notice dealing with <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> problems at nuclear power plants, agency records show. The agency reported Feb. 4, 1987, that wires wrapped with <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> had shorted out because of `` insulation degradation'' on two occasions at separate plants. The wires were in small electric motors that regulated the opening and closing of steam supply valves at the plants.
