<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG EATON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> thought a clump of grass got caught in his car's suspension during a camping trip. But he was in for a surprise when he tried to remove the object. `` I touched it and it moved _ and then I moved, too!'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, 33, said Monday. `` I thought it was a snake or something.'' The `` grass'' turned out to be a hedgehog, a small, spiny, porcupine-like mammal. The hedgehog hitched 350 miles underneath the car last weekend before <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> found the prickly little beast curled up in the suspension. `` I thought it was grass,'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said he found the hedgehog while cleaning the car and his camping trailer after a seven-hour drive from <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION>, in southwestern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eaton </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Nottingham </LOCATION> in the north. `` I dropped a screwdriver under the car,'' he said. `` The hedgehog really surprised me.'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, a sheet-metal worker, dismantled the suspension and removed the frightened animal, taking care not to touch it. He fed the `` ravenous'' little creature cat food and milk. The <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> for the Prevention of Cruelty of Animals later picked up the hedgehog and planned to release it in the countryside, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said. Hedgehogs, which grow to a foot in length including the tail, are covered with sharp spines and often roll into a ball when alarmed. They inhabit the undergrowth in woodlands and along the edges of fields and rarely venture out in daylight.
