<HEAD>Volcker Says World Bank May Wither Away Unless U.S. Contributes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, the former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, says the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is in danger of fading away as the biggest source of aid to the Third World unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acts soon to make a new contribution. The bank, headed by <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON>, a former congressman from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, wants a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pledge of $ 70.1 million a year over the next six years for a badly-needed increase in its capital. `` Our influence and leadership within the bank are certainly at stake, and I would raise the question,'' <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> told a news conference on Monday, `` if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is not going to participate in capital increases ... whether the bank itself can survive over a long period of time.'' So far, 140 of the 151 governments that own the bank have decided to contribute. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has urged approval of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contribution, but it has been held up in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by disagreement over what should be done to handle the bulk of the Third World's $ 1.2 trillion debt.
