<HEAD>Senate Votes Delay on Use of Device To Protect Turtles From Fish</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Nets
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal rules requiring shrimp fishermen to use devices to prevent sea turtles from being snared and drowned in nets would be delayed until next year under a compromise approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Monday gave voice vote approval to a compromise worked out by opponents and backers of the regulation. The amendment proposed by Sen. <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, D-Ala., says shrimp boats would not have to use turtle excluder devices in offshore waters before May 1, 1989, or in inshore waters before May 1, 1990 The agreement allows debate to move forward on legislation to reauthorize and strengthen the Endangered Species Act, which has technically been without legislative authorization since Oct. 1, 1985. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders gave no indication when they expected to complete work on the reauthorization bill.
