<HEAD>New Regulations Adopted For Horse Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Horse shows for all breeds will be able to continue under new Agriculture Department regulations that were supported by horse organizations, according to Sen. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>. Horse shows for many breeds were closed earlier this year after the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> filed a lawsuit seeking enforcement of regulations, primarily for walking horses, that had adversely affected much of the industry. `` These recommendations were reached after weeks of negotiations with every major horse organization throughout the country,'' <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ky </LOCATION>, said Monday. `` Now that the regulations are permanent, horse shows throughout <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and the nation can continue without the fear of being shut down.'' Major provisions of the new regulations include a new uniform standard for pads that would apply to all horse breeds; new rules on pad material; rejection of a proposal by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to further limit the weight of horseshoes; and new guidelines on examination procedures for horses exhibited in walking horse shows.
