<SECOND>PM-Sniffing Mouse,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animator Gives In, Cuts Mighty Mouse Flower Sniffing Scene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An animator has given in to a conservative media watchdog group and cut a segment from a Mighty Mouse cartoon, but maintains the scene shows the cartoon character sniffing flowers, not snorting cocaine. `` These 3 -LCB- seconds of footage have been taken totally out of context by individuals who seem to be searching for sinister undertones in a cartoon,'' animator <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakshi </PERSON> said in a statement Monday. `` Some have chosen to interpret the frames as showing a character using drugs,'' continued <PERSON> Bakshi </PERSON>, who won an Action for Children's Television award for the Mighty Mouse series on <ORGANIZATION> CBS-TV </ORGANIZATION>. `` Nothing could be further from the truth.'' But the Rev. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, called <PERSON> Bakshi </PERSON>'s decision a victory for his group. `` This is a de facto admission that indeed Mighty Mouse was snorting cocaine,'' <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> said from his <LOCATION> Tupelo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, office. `` We have been vindicated by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> itself.'' <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> on Monday also demanded <PERSON> Bakshi </PERSON>'s removal as producer of the Saturday morning cartoon and reiterated his call for the firing of <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for children's programming. He asked for a public apology by the network because of the April 23rd episode, titled `` The Littlest Tramp.'' <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> said the cartoon has been rerun twice and will be shown again, but no date was given. The 11-minute episode involves Mighty Mouse's efforts to save <PERSON> Polly </PERSON>, `` a poor but industrious flower seller,'' from a villain who destroys her flowers. Just before vanquishing the villain, Mighty Mouse either sniffs cocaine -LRB- according to <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> -RRB- or inhales the aroma of flowers `` in typical cartoon fashion'' -LRB- according to CBS -RRB-. `` Mighty Mouse was happy after smelling the flowers because it helped him remember the little girl who sold it to him fondly,'' said <PERSON> Bakshi </PERSON>, creator of the X-rated `` Fritz the Cat'' animated movies in the 1970s. `` But even if you're right, their accusations become part of the air we breathe. And that's why I cut the scene. I ca n't have children wondering if Mighty Mouse is using cocaine.'' <PERSON> Bakshi </PERSON> said the work of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> `` is the same thing'' as McCarthyism. `` The principal thrust of this episode is to show the redeeming quality of love and kindness,'' said <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> Entertainment President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> LeMaster </PERSON> in a statement supporting <PERSON> Bakshi </PERSON>. `` There is nothing in the story line, the dialogue or the behavior of Mighty Mouse that would suggest otherwise.'' <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> last year pressured <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> into scrapping plans for a cartoon based on the `` Garbage Pail Kids'' cards. Other targets of the fundamentalist preacher have been the `` Bloom County'' comic strip, and adult magazines like Penthouse and <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION>. The 7-11 and Stop-n-Go convenience store chains dropped Penthouse and <ORGANIZATION> Playboy </ORGANIZATION> in part due to pressure from <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON>.
