<FIRST>r i PM-SKorea-Beef     07-26 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SKorea-Beef,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Lifts Import Ban On Beef</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government sought to cool trade tensions today by lifting a 3-year-old ban on imported beef, but limited this year's shipments to 14,500 tons. Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> <PERSON> Kun-hwan </PERSON>, who made the announcement, did not say how much beef will be imported after this year, but indicated imports will be limited in order to protect the local beef industry. Officials said the government will maintain an import quota system, which has been opposed by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The end to the import ban was designed to avoid trade friction with foreign countries while at the same time alleviating domestic beef shortages, <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has been pressing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to drop the ban on beef and many other imports to help correct <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s $ 10 billion trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. There was no immediate reaction from local farmers who have strongly opposed imports of beef unless the government guaranteed a definite price support system before lifting the import ban. Many Korean farmers went bankrupt due to an excessive import of foreign beef cattle before the last ban was imposed in 1985. Farmers have staged demonstrations to demand retention of the import ban. Imported beef will be stockpiled in case the government needs to stabilize prices if domestic sales prices exceed designated levels, <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> has said previously that this year's proposed quota will include 3,000 tons of high-quality American beef for tourist hotels. Officials said that beef could start arriving next month.
</TEXT>
