<HEAD>Castro Marks 35th Anniversary of Revolution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Main ceremony scheduled to begin at 5 p.m. EDT; no lead
planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> today marks the 35th anniversary of his revolutionary fight to power, facing a battle against inefficiency that has dogged the economic performance of his communist state. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> traditionally gives his most important speech of the year on the anniversary of his failed effort to take the <PERSON> Moncada </PERSON> garrison here on July 26, 1953. He came to power less than six years later, on Jan. 1, 1959. The government has a 2-year-old `` rectification campaign'' to eradicate employee absenteeism, low productivity and other signs of inefficiency in the island nation's economy. But domestic commercial production fell by 3.2 percent last year, while <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s foreign debt grew by $ 671.8 million to $ 5.6 billion. The economy is heavily dependent on the sugar industry, which has suffered poor harvests for three consecutive years because of severe drought. In marked contrast to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` perestroika,'' or restructuring that involves economic liberalization, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has moved away from economic incentives and loosening state economic controls to focus on moral persuasion in a bid to increase productivity `` I do n't see why one thing should be linked with the other,'' <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, editor of the Cuban <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> monthly magazine <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Militante </ORGANIZATION>, told foreign correspondents Monday when asked about the apparent differences between Cuban and Soviet policy. `` The problems are our problems ... stemming from our own situation,'' he said. <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said that political work was neglected in favor of economic incentives in the decade preceding the rectification campaign. The government implemented, then abandoned, such experiments as a restricted free market for agricultural goods. `` The formation of the New Man was lost a little,'' <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said. Although a possible <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> agreement with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> that could lead to the withdrawal of nearly 50,000 Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> has drawn heavy international attention, officials in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> have been reluctant to discuss the issue and there is little mention of ongoing talks in the domestic news media. Cuban newspapers instead have focused almost entirely on the anniversary celebration, including extensive historical recollections of the failed battle and the startlingly young faces of <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> and his companions 35 years ago. The attack <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> led on the <PERSON> Moncada </PERSON> military barracks in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s second city after <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, failed. But the brutality with which it was suppressed by the regime of <PERSON> Fulgencio </PERSON> <PERSON> Batista </PERSON> triggered popular support for <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s later revolutionary insurrection. Celebration plans called for Pioneer Youth groups to recreate each step of the <PERSON> Moncada </PERSON> attack. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has been in the <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> area since last week to inaugurate public works projects, including the nation's second oil refinery, built with Soviet help, and a new hotel held up as an example of what can be done to expand the tourist industry and attract badly needed foreign exchange. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> timed the attack on <PERSON> Moncada </PERSON>, now a museum and elementary school, to coincide with the traditional Carnival celebration to take government forces by surprise. Carnival still is celebrated these days simultaneously with the <PERSON> Moncada </PERSON> anniversary.
