<HEAD>Pupils From Poor Chicago School Leaving for Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Students board buses at 2:30 p.m EDT; Yo-seanda in 10th graf
is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten elementary school pupils from one of the city's poorest, roughest neighborhoods were leaving for a three-country tour of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> after studying French and raising $ 30,000 for the trip. The pupils at <ORGANIZATION> Suder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> have worked since October, studying African culture after school and getting shots, passports and visas in preparation for their departure this afternoon, Principal <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Daigre </PERSON> said Monday. The children, aged 11 to 14, will make a one-day stopover in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. Then it's on to <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Abidjan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Lome </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Togo </LOCATION>. They are scheduled to return to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Aug. 9. In preparing for their trip, the youngsters have heard African speakers and visited the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> branch at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> here, Mrs. <PERSON> Daigre </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` We taught them how to set long-range goals,'' and how to meet short-term goals along the way, she said. `` I think we have made them much more sophisticated about meeting people ... how to carry themselves.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Daigre </PERSON>, one of five adults going on the trip, helped organize it. She said setting up travel to any country would be instructive for the students, but that for students from an all-black school it would be particularly beneficial to visit countries dominated and run by blacks. `` I have traveled extensively, and nothing hit me as hard as when I went to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' said the principal, who also is black. `` There is a kinship that you feel, there is an openness that you feel. `` I felt as though I went home, I really did,'' she said. <PERSON> Yo-seanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Baines </PERSON>, 13, who will be an eighth-grader at <LOCATION> Suder </LOCATION> this fall, said she's anxious to meet people in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and see `` how they dress and the food they eat.'' She also wants to see what houses and clothes look like in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Yo-seanda's mother, <PERSON> Vernya </PERSON> <PERSON> Baines </PERSON>, said she thinks the trip will be a `` beautiful experience'' for her daughter, who has never been on an airplane or traveled out of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. `` We're poor, but I think it'll give them a chance to see people that are poorer than we are,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Baines </PERSON> said. `` Maybe she'll appreciate some of the things she maybe takes for granted. More than $ 30,000 was raised for the trip from churches, community groups and fund-raising events such as candy sales, said Mrs. <PERSON> Daigre </PERSON>, who is paying her own way. The cost for each child is $ 2,700. School officials told the students that some <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> cities would look much like <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities, and that the old stereotype of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as a land of villages and huts may not apply, Mrs. <PERSON> Daigre </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> Abidjan </LOCATION> is referred to as the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' she said. `` When you go downtown, you think you are in a small, metropolitan city. `` The lesson from that is travel and find out for yourself.''
