<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s most powerful leaders met today to discuss a successor to Ne Win as chairman of the country's ruling <ORGANIZATION> socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, sources said. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> gathered to choose successors to Ne Win and party Vice Chairman <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu </PERSON>, the country's two most powerful figures, the sources said on condition of anonymity. The 77-year-old Ne Win, who came to power in a 1962 military coup, announced abruptly Saturday that he was resigning. He cited his age and violent anti-government rioting in March and June as key factors in his decision. The Central Committee, elected in 1985, includes about 270 members and normally abides by decisions made by the party's most powerful body _ the 15-member Central Executive Committee. The most senior member of the executive committee, party General Secretary <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON>, is considered Ne Win's likely successor. No details of the meeting were available. It comes one day after a special party congress concluded its meetings on sweeping reform proposals. The three-day congress session ended Monday with a vaguely worded announcement, possibly reflecting splits within the party over the dramatic events of recent days. The official <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> said delegates `` firmly suggested'' against a voter referendum on whether <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s 26 years of one-party rule should be replaced by a multi-party system. The rejection of Ne Win's recommendation for the referendum was the first known time the party had not rubber-stamped his proposals. Some liberalization of the economy last year has failed to stop <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s downward spiral. Inflation is soaring, government stores are virtually empty and the country is saddled with a foreign debt of about $ 4 billion.
