<HEAD>Hamadi Sent Postcard From Greece One Day Before Athens Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> sent a postcard from <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> the day before the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> airliner he is accused of hijacking departed from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, according to evidence introduced today. The postcard, introduced by prosecutors during <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s trial on air piracy and murder charges, was dated June 13, 1985, and had been sent to the brother of <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s West German girlfriend. <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> flight 847 was hijacked on June 14, 1985, and diverted to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, after it had departed <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver was fatally shot and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days. The postcard was read by Chief Judge <PERSON> Heiner </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueckenberger </PERSON> at the start of the fourth week of <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s trial in a courtroom on a <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> prison compound on charges of hijacking, murder and possession of explosives. The postcard, written in German, is addressed to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, brother of <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s former West German girlfriend, <PERSON> Birgit </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for two years until November 1984. The postcard carries a stamp June 13, 1985, and reads: `` I send you this card after seven months because you are my friend and brother. Take care of my daughter <PERSON> Lydia </PERSON>. Your brother <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>.'' In the text, <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> purportedly wrote: `` Today is my birthday and I am now in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Mueckenberger </PERSON> said the postcard was sent from <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. <PERS