<HEAD>Zoo Plans Unprecedented Effort to Save Expected Panda Cub</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION>, where four panda cubs have been stillborn or died shortly after birth, said today an unprecedented technological effort is planned to save the expected offspring of female giant panda Ling-Ling. `` We're, in fact, taking a step that's altogether unprecedented, but really on the best medical advice,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, the zoo's director, in an interview on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America''. <PERSON> Ling-Ling </PERSON>, who lives with her mate <LOCATION> Hsing-Hsing </LOCATION> in the zoo's <ORGANIZATION> Panda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, gave birth to three stillborn cubs before giving birth to a live cub last year Zoo employees' hopes were raised when that baby was born apparently healthy and screaming lustily, but the cub died four days later. `` What happened last year is that the baby had no immune system,'' said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. `` When we did the autopsy, -LRB- we found -RRB- there were no immunoglobulins in the baby's blood. And that means that it had no protection against any kind of bacteria that it could encounter in the world around it.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said zoo officials, who in the past have not intervened with panda births for fear of alienating the mother from her baby, will be aggressive from the start this year. They believe the female panda will give birth this weekend or early next week. `` We're going to remove the baby from the mother and inject it with immunoglobulins we've extracted from his -LRB- <LOCATION> Hsing-Hsing </LOCATION>'s -RRB- blood, and hope that that will confer a greater immunity than the last one had,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` We're going to be extraordinarily careful about that, of course,'' he added. `` The baby will be removed by our veterinarians wearing surgical gloves and gowns and masks in the usual way, so it should n't acquire any human odor. And we will treat it before we return it to Ling-Ling with materials from the mother so that it acquires her odor.'' Zoo offiicals believe <PERSON> Ling-Ling </PERSON> is pregnant because she mated with <LOCATION> Hsing-Hsing </LOCATION> three times in April during her brief annual period of fertility, according to <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. He said her hormone levels are similar to those she displayed at this stage in her pregnancy last year. Zoo officials believe the 19-year-old <PERSON> Ling-Ling </PERSON> is nearing the end of her childbearing years. Nobody knows how many years pandas are fertile, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` The estimates are between 19 and 23 or 24 years. But there are no good longevity records on pandas from anywhere in the world, so that's just ` guess-timating'.'' Only about 1,000 of the endangered giant pandas are alive in the world today, including just 14 outside of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
