<HEAD>USIA Hints U.S. Will Abandon Cultural Exchange Treaty Over Court
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may abandon an international cultural exchange agreement if it loses a court battle with documentary filmmakers over allegations of censorship, a federal official suggested in a court filing. The threat by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, is the latest development in a battle over allegations the agency has hampered international distribution of documentaries with liberal themes. Movies that are certified by the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> as being of an educational, scientific or cultural nature are exempt from import duties in some 60 countries under a 40-year-old international treaty known as the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> Agreement. The suit, filed in December 1985 on behalf of makers of movies on subjects ranging from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to nuclear power, accuses the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> of, in effect, censoring the work of liberal moviemakers by making it more expensive to export their work. Two courts have sided with the moviemakers, ordering the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> to rewrite its rules for determining whether a movie is of an educational, scientific or cultural nature. If the government fails to get the rulings reversed, <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> said in a statement to be filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, `` it is my intent to recommend that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> terminate its participation in the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> Agreement.'' An attorney for the seven moviemakers in the case, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, called <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>'s response unreasonable `` It's like the kid with the football who says, ` If I ca n't win the game, I'm taking the ball home,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials handling the case did not respond to a telephone request for comment. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Tashima </PERSON> sided with the moviemakers in 1986, ruling that the <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> policies violated the moviemakers' constitutional rights to free speech. He ordered the agency to redraft its rules. Last May, <PERSON> Tashima </PERSON> rejected new rules, which included a provision allowing the government to brand a movie propaganda. The <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> has appealed that ruling and has asked the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, which upheld a challenge to <PERSON> Tashima </PERSON>'s original ruling, to reconsider. <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> wrote that the redrafted rules were a good-faith attempt to implement the court order and that broadening the rules further would amount to abandoning the treaty. In keeping with its interpretation of the treaty, the agency demanded that movies that advocate a point of view acknowledge that another point of view exists, <PERSON> Wick </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said his organization, a public interest lawyers group, and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> have drafted a proposed set of rules for movie certification, but <ORGANIZATION> USIA </ORGANIZATION> officials had refused to consider it.
