<SECOND>PM-Korea-Strike,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Police Foil Strike By Train Engineers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police today arrested about 1,400 striking locomotive engineers and their relatives whose protests paralyzed the national railway system. Police said thousands of riot police were mobilized to disperse sit-ins by engineers and their supporters at railway stations in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and other cities. The strikers were demanding higher pay and shorter working hours. In <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, hundreds of police stormed a <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> building and arrested about 300 engineers. No clashes were reported. Police said they would release most of the detainees, but that others would be charged with illegal activity under laws banning wildcat strikes by government officials. The state-run <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>, a government agency, said the strike _ which began shortly after midnight _ disrupted about 90 percent of normal daily service of 2,050 trains and affected more than 1 million passengers. The engineers, who earn an average of $ 1,230 a month, are demanding a 100 percent increase in wages, including overtime. About 4,400 train engineers and their assistants work for the national railroad. The railroad management has offered the workers a reduction in working hours from the current average of 245 hours to 224 hours a month, in addition to monthly raises from about $ 100 to about $ 138.
