<HEAD>Jack Clark, Announcer for ``Wheel Of Fortune,'' Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Veteran announcer <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the announcer for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s popular `` Wheel of Fortune'' game show, has died following a long battle with bone cancer. He was 62. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> died Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the show. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> introduced Wheel hosts <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Sajak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vanna </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. He also announced the show's contestants, described prizes and named the show's sponsors. Ms. <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> said many fans had written letters asking about <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> after he left the show several months ago. `` His voice was so well-known,'' she said. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> began his career in broadcasting more than 40 years ago, and received his first professional job as a substitute radio announcer at <ORGANIZATION> KROW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>. After graduating, he worked as a staff announcer for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> radio. By 1952, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> had moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where he became the program announcer for the TV game shows `` Password,'' `` To Tell The Truth,'' `` Split Second'' and `` The $ 25,000 Pyramid.'' In the 1970s, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> hosted TV game shows such as `` Dealer's Choice'' and `` The Cross-Wits. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and raised in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>, and four children.
