<HEAD>Union Drops Opposition To Detroit JOA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last newspaper union to oppose a proposed partial merger of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two major newspapers has dropped its objections, and backers say the plan now meets all requirements for federal approval. The Newspaper Guild of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> on Monday said it would not oppose a joint operating agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and The Detroit News after receiving concessions from the Free Press, according to <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Kummer </PERSON>, administrator of Newspaper Guild Local 22. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Anti-Trust Division and an adminstrative law judge, along with suburban <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> newspapers, remain opposed to the plan. Five other newspaper unions have endorsed the proposal. <ORGANIZATION> Knight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the News, filed a statement with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> saying the merger application meets the standards for approval set by the Newspaper Preservation Act The newspapers asked the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 for an exemption in antitrust law allowing them to merge business, advertising and circulation departments. Editorial departments would remain separate. A spokesman for Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who must rule on such exemptions, has said he will decide on it before he leaves office, which a spokesman has said will be by Aug. 15. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said Monday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the Guild's new position would not affect his ruling. He declined further comment. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> has said if <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> rejects the request, it would close the Free Press, resulting in the loss of 2,200 jobs. Both newspapers claim they have lost millions of dollars in recent years. The Guild's agreement with the Free Press reduces the number of Guild members to be laid off at the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> under a joint operating agreement from 100 to no more than 75. The agreement also guarantees the jobs of 45 maintenance workers at the News. The Guild represents about 650 editorial and business employees at the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and about 300 editorial workers at the News. The Guild filed a statement with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> which `` urges that the -LRB- merger -RRB- be approved.'' The statement said the union has become convinced `` that the closing of the Free Press is inevitable if the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> is not approved.'' Knight Ridder issued a statement Monday welcoming the Guild's decision News President and <PERSON> Publisher </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weil </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> declined to comment. The Free Press had 1987 circulation of 639,720 daily and 724,342 on Sundays, while circulation of the News was 678,720 daily and 839,319 on Sundays, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Audit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circulation </ORGANIZATION>.
