<HEAD>Mayor Orders Police To Shoot Park `Hoodlums' Caught Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS five grafs at end with other shoot orders</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WADLEY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor B.A. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> has ordered police to `` shoot to stop'' anyone caught fighting in the city's park. `` There has been too much fighting in the park _ young men from <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, young men from <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION>, young men from <LOCATION> Wadley </LOCATION> _ and the only way to break it up is for police to shoot them,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said Monday. The mayor said fighting in the 12-acre Hope Williams Memorial Park has been a frequent problem, but Sunday's brawl involving eight youths who used `` big sticks with nails driven in them'' as weapons prompted him to take action against such skirmishes. He said no one was seriously injured in the fight, but it presented a threat to the families and children who wanted to use the park as well as a threat to the town's reputation. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> has ordered an increased police patrol in the park during weekends. `` There will be a full-time policeman every Friday, Saturday and Sunday,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` They are to shoot from the waist down only.'' `` We're going to fix it so decent people can go to the park. All the hoodlums in <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION>, stay in <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` All the hoodlums in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, stay in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, and all the hoodlums in <LOCATION> Wadley </LOCATION> have been suspended from the park for the rest of the year.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said he also has increased the fine for fighting in the park from $ 71.50 to $ 125. Reports from the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said seven of the eight involved in Sunday's fight were juveniles and were turned over to juvenile authorities. The adult was charged with fighting and released on a $ 125 bond. <PERSON> Wadley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION> are in a rural area of eastern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> about 130 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s `` shoot to stop'' order is the latest in a series of such orders he has issued in the past three years. In 1986, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> issued a `` shoot to wound'' order _ instructing police officers to shoot suspected burglars from the waist down _ after a rash of burglaries in the east <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> town of 2,700. In 1985, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> ordered police to shoot stray dogs on sight to control the animals, which city officials said roamed the streets in packs, destroyed property, snapped at children and howled at the moon. He even offered a bounty of $ 3 for every dog shot. No shooting ever took place and both orders were eventually rescinded. Also in 1985, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> ordered police to arrest anyone using profane language in public. The order was aimed at young people playing basketball in the city park whose games were frequently accompanied by loud streams of what then-City Administrator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> described as `` pure, unadulterated profanity.''
