<HEAD>Strike on at Seven Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of nurses and other hospital workers today struck seven hospitals in a contract dispute that focuses on health insurance benefits. Picket lines went up shortly after 6 a.m., union spokesman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. The strike was the first in the 50-year history of Local 250 of the Hospital and <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, which has 1,700 members. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, a lawyer representing the hospitals, said Monday that patients would not be affected by the walkout by licensed vocational nurses, aides, housekeepers and laundry workers. The six hospitals in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and one in neighboring <LOCATION> Daly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hired additional workers and also will use management employees, she said. Union officials disputed the hospitals' claim that patient care would not suffer. `` The union takes the stand that that attitude is irresponsible. You ca n't take away 1,700 workers from seven institutions and expect it not to have any effect,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Twarog </PERSON>, Local 250's chief negotiator As Affiliated Hospitals of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, the hospitals had negotiated with Local 250 for a new, two-year contract since February. A federal mediator adjourned talks Saturday because no progress had been made. Health insurance was the major issue in the dispute. Affiliated Hospitals offered full coverage at no cost to employees, but a new provision would require contributions of $ 30 a month from full-time employees for family benefits. Also at issue were wages, with Affiliated Hospitals offering 3 percent raises for vocational nurses and lower-tier employees and no increase for higher-tier workers. Pay currently ranges from $ 7.90 an hour for housekeeping, laundry and food service employees and hospital aides to $ 11.70 an hour for technicians and vocational nurses. Talks continued between six of the hospitals and about 2,000 registered nurses. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has voted to strike Aug. 2 if no agreement is reached. The hospitals are <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francis </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>, Children's, Pacific Presbyterian and Mt. Zion hospitals in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Seton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Daly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
