prime minister and attorney general dismissed from posts. Pick up
5th pvs, Ne Win.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s ruling party today chose its No. 4 ranked leader _ <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> _ as party chairman to replace <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, who wielded authoritarian power over this Southeast Asian nation for a quarter century. A brief news release said the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> elected the 64-year-old retired army general during a special session. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, a hardliner widely criticized for his ruthless handling of student demonstrations, has served as the party's joint general secretary since 1985. He also holds the government post of <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> secretary. His elevation to the country's top post appeared to dash hopes among the public here that Ne Win's retirement would lead to widespread reform of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s one-party, military-backed system. Shortly after the announcement, state radio reported that Prime Minister <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Kha </PERSON> and Attorney General <PERSON> Myint </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> had been dismissed from their posts after being found reponsible for bloody student riots here last March. It was <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> who was widely criticized in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> for the brutal suppression of those riots, in which 100 people are said to have been killed. The radio annoucement gave no further details. Ne Win asked to step down Saturday after 26 years in power. On Monday, a special party congress accepted his resignation and that of the second most powerful figure in the country _ party Vice Chairman <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu </PERSON>, also the country's president. The 77-year-old Ne Win, who came to power in a 1962 military coup, cited violent anti-government rioting in March and June, for which he acknowledged some reponsibility, and his age as reasons for stepping down. Today's news release said the vice chairmanship of the party was left vacant and <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON>, who some had expected to succeed Ne Win, retained the No. 3 job of general secretary. It was not clear why <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON> was passed over for the top job. A three-day special party congress ended Monday with little but vaguely-worded statements issued to the public, possibly reflecting splits within the party over recent events. After the congress ended the 1,061 delegates were suddenly summoned back _ some from areas outside <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> _ but the session did not reconvene. Official Radio <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> announced Monday that delegates had `` firmly suggested'' rejecting a referendum called by Ne Win which could have ended 26 years of one-party rule. It marked the first known instance in which the party did not rubber-stamp Ne Win's proposals. State radio announced late Sunday that an emergency parliament session would convene Wednesday, apparently to act on the referendum proposal. Although the parliament is empowered to order a referendum by majority vote, it is not expected to oppose the party decision. The emergency session could also deal with the appointment of a new president to replace <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yu </LOCATION>. By tradition a party leader who quits his party post also resigns his government job. The political changes in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> follow months of street riots and deepening public discontent over the country's deteriorating economic situation. Public anger peaked last October when the government withdrew several currency notes from circulation and failed to provide any compensation, sparking the first major riots in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> since 1974. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> commanded the military forces that brutally put down a student protest in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> last March in which more than 100 people are said to have died. Recently the government admitted that 41 protesters suffocated in a van after their arrests. He also commanded an army company which killed 22 students during anti-government demonstrations at <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in July 1962. Efforts to liberalize the economy last year failed to stop <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s downward spiral. Inflation is soaring, government stores are virtually empty and the country is saddled with a foreign debt of about $ 4 billion. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> was among several party members who offered their resignations alonmg with Ne Win last week. But the party congress rejected them, saying the leaders were still young enough to rule. Succeeding <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> as joint general secretary was <PERSON> Kyaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Htin </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> as well as deputy prime minister and defense minster.
