.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman who hijacked an airliner with 146 people aboard to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> 19 years ago has been arrested in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, where she has lived for five years under assumed names, authorities said. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Grinage </PERSON>, 39, was arrested Monday, said <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents, who added they have 14 aliases listed for her. She was living under the name of <PERSON> Haziine </PERSON> <PERSON> Eytina </PERSON> with her husband and five children. A hearing to certify <PERSON> Grinage </PERSON>'s identity was postponed until Wednesday. <PERSON> Grinage </PERSON>'s husband, <PERSON> Milo </PERSON> <PERSON> Eytina </PERSON>, told acting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Scully </PERSON> that a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> lawyer had agreed to represent his wife, but could not get to <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> today. <PERSON> Eytina </PERSON>, also a lawyer, said the identification of his wife as the hijacker was `` absolute poppycock.'' <PERSON> Grinage </PERSON> and her then-husband, <PERSON> Tyrone </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellington </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, took a 2-year-old boy hostage on an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on Jan. 2, 1969, then forced the pilot at gunpoint to fly to <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, authorities said. While running up the aisle, <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> shouted `` Black Power'' and `` <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>,'' according to authorities. None of the 138 passengers or eight crew members was hurt. Grinage and <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> were indicted on air piracy charges later that year, although