<HEAD>Yellowstone Blaze Heads Away from Old Faithful</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE conditions today at Yellowstone;
picks up 5th graf pvs, `Nearly 15...' Subs 15th graf pvs, `In the
Teton...' with 1 graf to UPDATE acreage burned.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto IDA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters today called in helicopters and said they would use natural barriers to try to maneuver a forest fire that burned within 10 miles of Old Faithful geyser in parched Yellowstone National Park. Helicopters slinging torches that spit a napalm-like substance were called in, and ground crews used meadows and streams as a wall against the fire, said Incident Commander <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplinger </PERSON>. A final decision on sending out the helicopters was expected later today. `` What we can do, we can go out to one side or the other of the head of a fire, and ignite fire and get it to building and have it draw the head of the fire in one direction or another,'' he said this morning. `` We would just be trying to further influence the fire. It's going in the direction that we want it to go, but the more we can get it going in a more northerly direction, the better,'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Smart </PERSON>, fire planning coordinator, said today About 450 firefighters moved into the area Monday, and by tonight the total was expected to swell to 800 to protect the Old Faithful complex of hotels and cabins from the North Fork fire, which covered more than 2,700 acres. While officials earlier had said the fire burned to within eight miles of the geyser, <PERSON> Caplinger </PERSON> said it was still 10 to 12 miles to the west today and burning toward the northeast. `` The fire will burn to the northeast and will miss the Old Faithful area,'' Fire Information Officer <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Poague </PERSON> predicted late Monday. `` We're not in as much jeopardy as we thought we were.'' Blazes in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s oldest national park have blackened about 52,400 acres of its 2.2 million acres, which is mostly in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>'s northwest corner but extends into <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> In addition to <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, wildfires burned in sections of seven other Western states and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. Nearly 15 miles southeast of Old Faithful, hot embers Monday night rained down on <LOCATION> Grant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, burning through power lines as the 4,500-acre Shoshone fire and the 3,000-acre Red fire approached the area. The fire did not damage a small hotel, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> staff apartments and several house trailers in the area because they were made of cinder block and other non-flammable materials, <PERSON> Poague </PERSON> said. The area was evacuated last weekend, along with the <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> campground nearly 10 miles to the southwest and the park's southern entrance was closed. At <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, the fires burned to within one-eighth of a mile of the campground, and crews hosed down structures to keep them from catching fire, <PERSON> Poague </PERSON> said. About 500 firefighters battled both blazes. The threat to the Old Faithful area had seemed more serious because of aerial surveys and misleading winds, <PERSON> Poague </PERSON> said. Ground winds blew the blaze northeast into backcountry where it could burn untended, away from the geyser that erupts every 30 to 100 minutes, <PERSON> Poague </PERSON> said. But another wind at a higher altitude blew smoke west, toward <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Faithful </LOCATION>, making it seem the blaze was headed that way. No services or accommodations at Old Faithful have been closed, but visitors have been advised such action may be necessary, said park spokeswoman <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Anzelmo </PERSON>. About 1,200 guests generally spend a night at the historic Old Faithful Inn, the Snow Lodge and cabins in the area around Old Faithful, said park Assistant Superintendent <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Clary </PERSON>. Crews also fought the 31,500-acre Clover Mist fire in the park's eastern half to keep it out of adjacent <ORGANIZATION> Shoshone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Poague </PERSON> said In the Teton Wilderness along <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s southern border, more than 700 firefighters made progress today along the northern side of the 24,400-acre Mink Creek fire, working to keep it from spreading into <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Meadows </LOCATION> and Shoshone, officials said. Precipitation at <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> is 7.5 inches below normal for the year, and the Old Faithful area got just 0.75 of an inch of rain in June, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. Other fires crackled across hundreds of acres of brush and forest elsewhere in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and in parts of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. Temperatures Monday climbed to more than 100 degrees in sections of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Firefighters in central and northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> mopped up dozens of little fires while more lightning strikes were reported in the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> range. Crews virtually extinguished a pair of fires in <LOCATION> Calaveras </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> that burned about 11,000 acres and eight homes, officials said. In <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, where more than 50 fires have charred about 1.2 million acres, firefighters were battling only 22 of the blazes. Among the many fires in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, one near <LOCATION> Waring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION>, east of <LOCATION> Kotzebue </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> northwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, had jumped in size by 10,000 acres, spreading to 207,000 acres, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said the blaze destroyed an unoccupied cabin and authorities were unsure if it was abandoned or in use. Fire lines were holding in check a 323,000-acre fire near <LOCATION> Livengood </LOCATION> in interior <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. It was just seven miles from the trans-Alaska oil pipeline, but the line was in no danger, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said.
