<TEXT>
 The government is dropping forfeiture proceedings against the owners of a top ocean research vessel that had been seized under the government's `` zero tolerance'' anti-drug policy, an attorney said. The multimillion-dollar vessel is being released because the <ORGANIZATION> Woods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> did n't know any drugs were aboard, according to its attorney, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Zvetina </PERSON>. <PERSON> Zvetina </PERSON> said he was notified Monday that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has decided to drop forfeiture proceedings. The vessel had been seized May 18 after Customs officers found a trace of marijuana and two drug-related pipes when the vessel returned from a trip off the coast of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Atlantis II, a 210-foot vessel that participated in the 1986 exploration of the sunken liner Titanic, had been allowed to continue its scheduled scientific voyages, but the institute was required to inform Customs of its movement pending the outcome of forfeiture proceedings. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the forfeiture proceedings will be formally terminated after Woods Hole pays the expenses of the seizure. However, <PERSON> Zvetina </PERSON> said the institute may not have to pay any expenses because its personnel operated the ship during the entire seizure period. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which has authority over <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION>, determined the institute was innocent because it had no knowledge of the drugs and had taken reasonable precautions to prevent a vi