<HEAD>Philip Berrigan Sentenced to Six Months in Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Peace activist <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON> was sentenced today to six months in jail in connection with an Easter demonstration aboard a warship in which the ship's missile launchers were `` symbolically disarmed.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> ordered about 40 of <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>'s supporters to leave the courtroom when the group began reading a statement One man was dragged from the courtroom, but there were no arrests. The demonstration continued in a hallway. <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>, 64, a former priest and longtime activist who resisted the draft during the Vietnam War and now operates a Christian peace mission in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, faced a maximum six months in prison on his conviction of misdemeanor trespassing. <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>, along with <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Boertje </PERSON>, 32, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, 27, and Sister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> McKenna </PERSON>, 57, were convicted by <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> in May of misdemeanor trespassing in connection with the demonstration aboard the battleship <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. The four `` symbolically disarmed'' the ship's cruise missile launchers by beating on them with hammers and smearing them with blood. They boarded the warship as part of an open house at the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION>, slipped away from their escorts and attacked the armored launchers, doing minor damage. The four are members of the anti-nuclear group Plowshares founded by <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>. The group claims the missiles are outlawed by international law, and that their actions to symbolically disarm the weapons were not illegal because they had no criminal intent. Sister <PERSON> McKenna </PERSON> received a two-year suspended sentence and was placed on probation on the condition she not enter a military establishment. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> received a 4-month sentence and <PERSON> Boertje </PERSON> a 6-month term. Both also were ordered to appear in federal court in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> for a probation violation hearing and <PERSON> Boertje </PERSON> for a fugitive warrant. <PERSON> Boertje </PERSON> is wanted for failing to appear at a 1987 sentencing for a similar demonstration. In that incident, protesters entered the <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and took hammers to several aircraft, doing more than $ 165,000 in damage. <PERSON> Boertje </PERSON> faces a possible 11 -LCB- - year sentence in that case
