<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Thunderstorms rumbled over much of the nation today, bringing rain to drought-parched land, after severe storms belted the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and South with tornadoes, lightning, hail and fierce winds that killed two people. A cold front hammered violent storms through the central <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Monday, producing severe weather in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, a late evening thunderstorm whipped up high winds that caused widespread damage around Pine Bluff. One person was killed when a tree was blown onto an occupied car. In <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, lightning struck and killed a <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> woman as thunderstorms packing winds up to 60 mph raced across the state's southeastern <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, knocking out power to thousands. Two tornadoes ripped through southeastern <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Monday afternoon and a third touched down a few hours later, uprooting trees and damaging crops near the eastern town of <LOCATION> Lapeer </LOCATION>. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, thunderstorms unleashed winds that downed large trees near Alma, <LOCATION> Saginaw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lapeer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and hail up to an inch in diameter. The storm knocked out power to 20,288 <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> customers in the southern <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>; power was restored this morning to all but 5,480 customers, company spokesman <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Farr </PERSON>. About 1,200 <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> cu