<HEAD>Error-Correcting Bill Wins Committee OK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> today approved a bill of several hundred pages designed to correct errors in the 1986 tax overhaul. Attached to the bill, which won unanimous approval, was a provision exempting farmers from paying the federal tax on diesel fuel they buy for off-road use. A 1987 change requires them to pay the tax of 15.1 cents a gallon and then apply for a refund at yearend. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the committee, said the `` technical corrections'' bill is too important to clutter with other amendments that might delay its enactment. But he said committee staff will attempt to put together a package of unrelated tax amendments that would be added to the bill when it reaches the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor, if a majority of committee members can agree. That presumably would include, for example, an amendment allowing free-lance writers and artists to deduct certain expenses even before a book or painting begins producing revenue. Another likely amendment would free owners of mutual fund shares from paying a tax on certain operating expenses of the fund. Those provisions and numerous others were added to the technical-corections bill by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, as were selected tax increases targeted to pay for the tax benefits. The House bill, for example, would impose a tax of $ 2.67 a pound on pipe tobacco and bar moonlighters and others who work out of their homes from deducting any part of their base monthly telephone bill.
