 The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s daily newspaper on Tuesday criticized advertisements on Italian television that recommend using condoms to prevent the spread of AIDS. The article in <PERSON> L'Osservatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> reaffirmed the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s opposition to promoting the use of condoms in the fight against acquired immune deficiency syndrome, declaring that, as with smoking, the best medical advice is abstinence The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> commentary said the theory of not striking at the roots of evil but only its consequences has resulted in the promotion of condoms as the `` routine remedy'' of dealing with what is presented as `` the evil of the century.'' In a major statement in March, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> newspaper said the issue of sexual permissiveness was the `` true cause'' of the AIDS problem. The latest commentary said the TV spots fit into the logic that `` the essential issue is not to prevent the evil but to control its effects.'' The spots, contracted by the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, begin Tuesday on <ORGANIZATION> RAI-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s three channels and run through Aug. 8, and then again in mid-September.
