<HEAD>Israeli Delegation To Moscow, First Visit in 21 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A team of Israeli diplomats, including a former Soviet dissident, left Tuesday for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in a visit seen here as critically important to <LOCATION> Soviet-Israeli </LOCATION> relations, which were severed 21 years ago. The five delegates plan to join in <LOCATION> Sabbath </LOCATION> prayers at the main synagogue on Friday evening in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and to make themselves highly visible among Soviet Jews, many of whom have been choosing to emigrate to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> instead of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, who met Tuesday with visiting Russian Orthodox Metropolitan Filaret, said he hoped for a substantial improvement in <LOCATION> Soviet-Israeli </LOCATION> relations. The visit will be especially emotional for two of the Israelis. Delegation head <PERSON> Meron </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> emigrated from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> at the age of 10, and <PERSON> Yaakov </PERSON> <PERSON> Kedmi </PERSON>, 43, is a former Soviet Jewish dissident who came here at the age of 24. `` We are both very moved,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, 41, said on <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>. `` When we left there, we were young. I do n't think either of us ever thought we could return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ certainly not as official representatives of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Yeshayahu </PERSON> <PERSON> Anug </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, spent the last year heading efforts aimed at gaining Soviet permission for the official Israeli visit. He called it a `` major event'' and added `` the atmosphere is promising ... but we do n't intend to conquer the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in one day.'' He said the immediate purpose of the delegation was to help process Israeli visas both for Soviets wishing to emigrate and those wishing to visit. From January to June, 6,017 Soviet Jews emigrated and 840 of those went to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, according to the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> Intergovermental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migration </ORGANIZATION>. In addition, the team will inspect the empty <ORGANIZATION> Israeli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> building, for which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> pays about $ 100,000 annual rent. <PERSON> Anug </PERSON> said the delegation's limited mandate could be expanded, although there was no plan for it to take part in political talks with Soviet officials. The diplomats traveled Tuesday to <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hague </LOCATION>, where they are to pick up two-month Soviet visas and then leave Thursday for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> hopes the delegates will be allowed to stay longer. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> severed ties with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> after the 1967 Middle East War to protest <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s occupation of territory captured from three Arab countries. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> still have no official diplomatic relations, but links between <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> have recently improved. In the summer of 1986, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> and Soviet delegates met in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, for the first official session since 1967. Last summer, a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> delegation arrived in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> on two-month visas that since have been extended.
