<DATELINE>VADUZ, Liechtenstein (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The tiny principality of <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION> on Tuesday marked the 50th anniversary of the coming to power of Prince <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s longest-reigning head of state. Parliament held a special session in honor of the 81-year-old monarch, and a portrait of the prince etched onto <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION> marble was unveiled in the government building in the capital, <LOCATION> Vaduz </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> is the second-longest ruling head of state in the world, behind <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, 87, who has reigned for 62 years. He oversees a 62-square-mile principality with a homogeneous population of 27,000. Four years ago, <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> turned over administrative duties to his eldest son, <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Adam </PERSON>, and since then his role largely has been ceremonial. Under <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Josef </PERSON>'s rule, <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION> moved from being a poor agrarian state to a modern industrial nation. The prince also is credited with resolving internal political unrest before World War II and with keeping the principality, nestled between <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, neutral during the war.
