<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> today side-stepped a controversial pension issue during debate on the fiscal 1989 health and human services spending bill, after having rejected attempts to terminate the nation's family planning program. The massive $ 137 billion bill, which also contains money for the departments of labor and education, is traditionally a lightning rod for controversy. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said he would veto the entire bill based on a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> provision permitting Medicaid funds for abortions where pregnancy is the result of rape or incest. Current law permits payments only where the life of the mother is endangered. Senators agreed today to leave out another provision opposed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, a one-year moratorium on companies cashing out overfunded pension plans. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> had approved the moratorium, but the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> instead passed a resolution directing the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to deal with the issue. Hundreds of companies have dipped into their plans and labor leaders say the money is often used for mergers or other business moves not in workers' interests. `` Company after company has turned its pension plan into a piggybank'' while paying meager benefits to retirees, said Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, chief sponsor of the provision. Sen. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Okla </LOCATION>., a leading opponent of the moratorium, said the <ORGANIZATION> Metzenbaum </ORGANIZATION> approach would have encouraged companies to underfund their plans He also said the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> had no expertise in the complicated area of pension law. Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, lost attempts Monday to eliminate the $ 140 million Title X family planning program and to require unmarried minors seeking contraceptives from federally funded clinics to have written parental consent. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 65-21 against getting rid of Title X and 54-34 against the mandatory parental consent proposal. In other action Monday on the labor-HHS spending bill, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved by voice vote an abortion `` conscience clause'' sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, R-N. The provision says none of the money in the bill can be used to require any person or entity to perform or facilitate abortions. It applies to medical personnel or denominational hospitals with religious or moral objections to abortion. Title X provides money to states, local health departments and private groups for family planning clinics serving primarily low-income women. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> alleged that Title X recipients are using federal funds for abortion-related services and for `` secret sex programs for our nation's teen-agers.'' `` The federal government takes money from American parents and then uses that money to give contraceptives ... to their children,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. `` This is wrong. This is immoral.'' Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, R-Conn., countered that `` Title X is not an abortion program It's a knowledge program. It has been enormously successful.''
