 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday stripped away all issues of controversy and unanimously approved a bill correcting hundreds of errors in the 1986 tax overhaul law. The chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, won quick approval of the bill by promising colleagues that the committee staff would attempt to put together a separate package of their favorite unrelated tax provisions. If such a package could win approval of a majority of the panel, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, it could be offered as an amendment when the bill reaches the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor, perhaps in September. That package likely would include amendments to permanently free about 20 million mutual fund shareholders from a tax on certain fund operating expenses and to allow free-lance writers and artists to deduct expenses before a book or painting starts producing income. Most of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s bill is designed to correct mistakes in the 1986 law, but there is a new provision which would exempt farmers and some other diesel users from paying tax on fuel used for off-road purposes. A 1987 law requires that such users pay the tax of 15.1 cents a gallon and apply for a refund at year-end. `` This is the last major piece of legislation we expect to come out of this committee this year,'' said <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, the running mate of Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. He cautioned that many tax incentives that members want to add to the bill can not be accepted because of budget constraints. While members of the committee probably would have no trouble agreeing on some relatively small selective tax increases, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, the problem would come in deciding which of many pet tax incentives would go into the final bill. `` Unless we follow what you suggest,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, senior Republican on the committee, `` we will have no bill at all.'' The committee's action left in doubt the fate of several major provisions that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> added to its own version of the `` technical corrections'' bill. These include tax credits for business research and experimentation, for owners of low-income rental housing and for employers that hire the poor, as well as a tax exemption for bonds used to help low-income families buy their first home. The Ways and <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also approved several tax increases to pay for those and other incentives. Those provisions range from a new tax of $ 2.67 on a pound of pipe tobacco to a reduction in tax benefits for single-premium life insurance policies. `` There is a whole litany of things we would like to do but were are not going to be able to get them in'' this bill, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. Accountants and tax lawyers are especially eager to have the technical-corrections bill enacted because many provisions in the massive 1986 law are unclear or ambiguous.
