<HEAD>NASA Selects Mississippi Sites For New Rocket Engine Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has selected two sites in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> as the best locations for proposed government-owned facilities for the production and testing of a new space shuttle solid rocket motor, the space agency announced today. A location in northeastern <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> known as <LOCATION> Yellow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> was selected as a production site for the space shuttle advanced solid rocket motor, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said, and the <ORGANIZATION> Stennis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, has been selected as a site for the testing of the motor. <LOCATION> Yellow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> is owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Stennis </PERSON> is a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> facility. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said work at the <LOCATION> Yellow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> site could provide about 1,400 new jobs, and an additional 600 jobs would be created at <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. The space shuttle advanced solid rocket motor is planned to replace the current redesigned shuttle rocket motor in the mid-1990s. The advanced motor is expected to provide more reliability and safety, and enable the space shuttle to carry more cargo into orbit. Under the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> advanced rocket motor plan, the space agency will now ask for contract proposals for work on the rocket motor at the two <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> sites. Companies will be asked to make bids on building a government-owned facility that would be operated by the contractor. Companies may also propose that the work be done in facilities built and owned by contractors at a privately owned site of the contractor's choosing. After evaluating the options, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> will make a final decision on the advanced solid rocket motor contract. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said that an advanced solid rocket motor program in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> will make `` maximum utilization'' of the Michoud Assembly Facility and the <ORGANIZATION> Slidell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complex </ORGANIZATION>, both located nearby in southeastern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>.
