<FIRST>r a AM-BackStudy     07-26 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Back Study,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Many Lower Back Disc Operations May Be Unnecessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The spine specialist who prescribed back surgery for football star <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Montana </PERSON> says at least twice as many operations as necessary are performed for ruptured discs in the lower back. Dr. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Saal </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said surgeons generally use the wrong criteria in deciding to operate. He reported findings of his three-year study, co-written with his brother, Dr. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Saal </PERSON>, to the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, on Monday. These include severe pain, leg weakness, failure to respond to bed rest and diagnostic exams showing a fragment of the disc's nucleus has broken through the disc wall and is pressing against a nerve root None of those, <PERSON> Saal </PERSON> said, should be used as overwhelming evidence that surgery is needed. Instead, the decision should be based on the patients' level of function and whether that can be improved by an active rehabilitation program, he said. `` More than 20 percent of patients with -LRB- lower back -RRB- disc problems have surgery but less than 10 percent may really need it if there are no other problems, such as stenosis, or narrowing of the spine,'' <PERSON> Saal </PERSON> said in an interview. Other studies have noted the presence of stenosis as a reason for failed lumbar disc surgery and estimated the presence of stenosis in 30 percent of those patients. Rapid, progressive weakness in the leg is an indication surgery is needed, <PERSON> Saal </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> had those symptoms, along with stenosis, before his surgery in 1986. <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s back surgery was so successful, it was commonly referred to on the sports pages as a `` miracle.'' At mid-season, doctors said the surgery would sideline him for the rest of the year, possibly forever. But he was back on the field in weeks to lead the 49ers in the playoffs. Most patients with ruptured lumbar discs have less severe symptoms and can return to work and sports within four months after starting active, non-operative treatment, <PERSON> Saal </PERSON> said. `` He's probably correct,'' said <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Conley </PERSON>, chief of neurosurgery at the <ORGANIZATION> Palo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and associate professor of surgery at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Far too much surgery has been done on lumbar discs, and we're becoming more aware about how much it's been overdone now because we have better tools, such as magnetic resonance imaging.'' <PERSON> Saal </PERSON>'s treatment included teaching patients how to reduce the risks of further injury, training for spine stabilization and exercises to develop overall body strength and flexibility while the disc heals itself. Injections or drugs sometimes were used to block pain and reduce swelling. Such treatment, he said, can cost up to $ 3,500, compared with more than $ 30,000 for surgery and post-operative care, while involving much less risk. More than 2 million Americans suffer from ruptured discs in their necks and lower backs, and they spend more than $ 3 billion annually on lumbar disc treatment, according to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthopedic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgeons </ORGANIZATION>. An estimated 237,000 operations on discs in the neck and back were performed in 1986, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Mortara </PERSON>, neurosurgeon at <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and associate professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, said he agreed that lumbar disc surgery is sometimes performed unnecessarily but was unaware of any studies indicating how often that occurs. But he was skeptical of <PERSON> Saal </PERSON>'s claim that 90 percent of lumbar disc patients could be healed without surgery if they have severe pain. `` We're quite conservative here, as a rule,'' he said. `` But if the patients have failed bed rest, physical therapy, pain medication, antispasm drugs and are out of work and ca n't do the things they like, then surgery is probably indicated.'' <PERSON> Saal </PERSON>'s study, based on 59 patients averaging 35 years old and thought to be free of stenosis, found their symptoms _ sciatic pain in their toes, legs or buttocks, a tingling sensation in their toes and weakness in their feet _ lasted an average of five months. Only six patients required surgery after the non-operative program, but four of those were found to have stenosis. Eighteen patients asked surgeons for a second opinion of their cases and all were recommended for surgery as soon as possible to avoid long term complications. Fifteen of those, however, rated themselves good or excellent after treatment without surgery.
</TEXT>
