<HEAD>Neglected Span Reopened After Surface Facelift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, closed when inspectors discovered such extensive corrosion they feared it might collapse, was reopened Tuesday following nearly $ 10 million in surface work. `` The bridge is now stronger than it's been since World War II,'' said Transportation Commissioner <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON>, who watched the first cars roll over the span linking <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> at 7:45 a.m. The bridge was built in 1903 for bicycles and horse-drawn buggies. By the time it was closed April 12 it was carrying more than 100,000 vehicles and 420 trains daily. The closing of the bridge affected millions of daily commuters not only on that structure but on the neighboring <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> bridges, to which displaced traffic was rerouted. Two lanes for motorists were opened in May and another two in June. Tuesday's ceremony marked the opening of all eight lanes to cars. Brooklyn-bound trucks remain forbidden, but should be allowed on the bridge by mid-August, <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON> said the city was able to complete the work two weeks ahead of schedule because contractors and city employees worked seven days a week, adding some 150 tons of steel to the structure. More extensive, long-term work _ particularly on the approach roadways leading to the bridge _ is still needed, <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON> said. A $ 350 million, seven-year project will begin once federal and state funds are secured. Closures then will be one lane at a time, he said. `` We now know what we need to do to preserve this bridge,'' said <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON>. `` When we're done it will be like new and should last hundreds of years _ if we take care of it.''
