<HEAD>Cholera Spreads, Many Of The 157 Dead Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contaminated rainwater in the slums of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> is blamed by city officials for an epidemic of water-borne diseases that killed 14 more lives Tuesday, bringing the death toll to 157. At least 317 people suffering from gastroenteritis and cholera were hospitalized Tuesday and that the epidemic is spreading to new areas of the Indian capital. More than 4,400 residents, mostly children, are hospitalized with the diseases, caused by contaminated water from monsoon rains that has seeped into the city's primitive pipes and wells. About 1,200 new cases were reported Monday from nine areas of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> with a combined population of half a million people. Most of the earlier cases were reported from only two neighborhoods. More than 11,700 people have sought treatment since July 9. Officials say they have inoculated more than 200,000 people to halt the spread of the diseases. Dr. <PERSON> Raj </PERSON> <PERSON> Saxena </PERSON>, a physician in the district of <PERSON> Sunder </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagri </PERSON>, says he and his team are inoculating 30 people every hour. `` But it seems it's not working,'' he said. `` Frankly speaking, the situation is out of our hands. The damage has been done, we are just trying to check it.'' Hit hardest by the epidemic are slums built after 1975 in outlying areas to the east. Of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>'s 8 million people, 2.4 million people live in slums, 25 percent of which have no power supply, 49 percent no tap water and 32 percent no toilet facilities. The impoverished <LOCATION> Nand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nagri </LOCATION> district, east of the <LOCATION> Yamuna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, was the first area hit by the epidemic and is worst-affected. It has 50,000 residents. Garbage in the area has not been collected for four or five months after a dispute between the <ORGANIZATION> Delhi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> over which agency was responsible for the slum areas. Health officials say rain water flowing through garbage and sewage into shallow wells is spreading the diseases among the congested dwellings. Health officials ordered city wells shut off and water tanked in. Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> toured the area last week and ordered the garbage cleared. But the <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported Tuesday that the slums `` still looked like cesspools.'' Dr. T.S. <PERSON> Rana </PERSON>, a private physician with a clinic in <LOCATION> Nand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nagri </LOCATION>, said the number of cases may be greater than reported. `` At least four to five people are dying of cholera from this area daily who are not reported,'' he said. `` People here do not have money to take patients to hospitals,'' he said. `` They try the local doctors and then just pray, and cholera is a disease which does not respond to prayer.'' The monsoon rains began in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> in the last week of June.
