n the country followed under <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>. Explaining <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s economic problems, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said the country had not moved fast enough on the political front to expand the rights of the individual workers and factory managers to make their own decisions. `` Political without economic reform, no, it's not possible,'' he said, speaking through a translator. On the same theme, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said, `` The two processes must be fitted to each other. You can not separate them practically. Political and economic endeavors take place in one body.'' He said writers were gaining more freedom and all Hungarians were able to express their views, although the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> also retains the right to do so. At the same time, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> said works by Hungarian expatriates were not permitted into the country `` if they are against the constitution'' and that he was against removing <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> from the Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>. Speculation that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would withdraw the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> unilaterally from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has circulated for at least a month. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, citing intelligence sources, kept the rumors moving. But they have not panned out. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>'s remarks suggested <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would blend any withdrawal from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> into larger negotiations between <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact on an overall reduction of conventional troops, armor and aircraft in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. No date has been set for negotiations, with the chief stumbling block a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand that the Soviets agree to hold simultaneous talks about 