<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has landed a $ 3.6 billion contract for a computer system that will replace voice communications between air traffic controllers and pilots with electronic messages and eventually may usher in the use of computers to actually direct aircraft. The system, expected to be in full operation at the turn of the century, also would give controllers advance warning of overcrowded air traffic conditions. An <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> executive called the contract the largest ever received by the company and officials said it was the largest ever awarded by the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> bested <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, for the 10-year contract to develop the Advanced Automation System for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> had spent $ 233 million of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s money and about $ 80 million of its own in the competition. The system, which is to be developed by <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and more than a dozen subcontractors, is designed to provide controllers with more modern computer capacity and flexibility to handle increased air traffic loads. The project outlined in the contract is expected to be completed in 1998, although other enhancements are likely to be made after that to meet additional requirements, officials said. The new system is to be introduced in 1992 when it is scheduled to be installed at the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s air traffic control center in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> called the new system `` a significant milestone and a historic step toward the future'' of air traffic control. The new computer system and radar screens will allow controllers to use modern computer terminals and provide clearer displays, weather information and eventually the means to predict when airspace is expected to become crowded, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Controllers eventually will communicate with aircraft by data link _ computer messages _ instead of by voice. Although planners envision eventual modifications that would allow the computers to talk directly to aircraft through data links, <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said there always will be `` a controller in the loop.'' The new technology will allow controllers `` to work smarter not harder,'' <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that the increased automation represented by the new system would reduce the number of additional controllers needed over the next 20 years. <PERSON> Mimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON>, deputy secretary of transporation, called the system to be provided by <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> `` an entirely new generation of air traffic control hardware and software'' that will `` provide the capacity needed for continually increasing air traffic well into the next century while substantially enhancing safety.'' She said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s Federal Systems Division was selected over <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ground </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> largely because its bid was lower. She declined to characterize how much lower the <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> bid was, except to say the government `` benefited a great deal -LRB- on costs -RRB- from the strong competition.'' `` Both bids were extremely competent technically,'' she told a news conference. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebker </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> vice president and head of its Systems Integration Division, said the contract `` is the largest contract that <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> has ever received'' either from the government or private industry. About 50 percent of the $ 3.6 billion project will be subcontracted to other companies, although a list of subcontractors has yet to be developed, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>, the project manager. Two of the biggest subcontractors will be <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, which will design and manufacture the consoles and display equipment, and <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, which will develop the software. First word of the contract being awarded to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> came in a one-sentence announcement late Monday, although at the time DOT officials refused to elaborate or provide additional details. The Advanced Automation System is the cornerstone of the government's broad-ranging air traffic control modernization program which is estimated to cost at least $ 16 billion when it is completed. Aviation experts have long complained that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s current computer equipment is outdated. Recently, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> completed installation of an interim computer system, also produced by <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> under a separate $ 197 million contract, which is to serve as a bridge until the more advanced system is available.
