 independent, full review of all the facts that have been presented in the inquiry and report back to the committee,'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> told reporters in a brief appearance outside the closed committee room. `` The fact that I'm a Democrat does n't stand in my way of being fair and full,'' he added. `` I would hope that no citizen would be branded unfair or unobjective simply because he exercised his basic American right.'' He said his selection was `` a great opportunity for me, and I appreciate the confidence the committee had. I'm going to do my very, very best. But <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, in response to a question, said <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> would not be authorized to go beyond the scope of the six-count resolution of inquiry unanimously adopted by the panel on June 9. That drew a complaint from Rep. <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, R-Ga., <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s chief accuser, who said no inquiry could be considered independent if it does not permit investigators to follow leads to their `` The independent counsel has to be truly independent,'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said. `` He can not be on a short leash held by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairman of the committee.'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> objected to the choice of <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>, whom he called a partisan Democrat. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> lawyer has been a fund-raiser for the presidential campaign of Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, according to an article in the January issue of the American Lawyer. <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>'s selection also was criticized by Citizens for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, which sent a Mailgram to the committee saying, `` The appointment of liberal Democrat activist <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> as outside counsel in the <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> case certainly calls into question the independence of the