event her spirit from escaping. He said the grave likely would be covered with salt and pins and that the victim's hands probably would be tied. `` Salt and pins were to keep her spirit confined, even in death, and that's why the expert was sure she was tied, too,'' said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. Authorities are hoping the expert will help them find <PERSON> Rubia </PERSON>'s body Her bloody prescription glasses were found in <PERSON> Toussaint </PERSON>'s pickup truck after he committed suicide. The <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> expert, a self-described `` good witch'' who police did not name, told officers the items are those used in voodoo, an African-born religion based on a belief in sorcery. The jars, molasses and spices were supposed to seal in bad spirits and prevent them from attacking <PERSON> Toussaint </PERSON>, the expert said. `` He wanted a barrier between him and her in both worlds,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Toussaint </PERSON>'s ex-wife said <PERSON> Toussaint </PERSON> was fearful of spirits when married to her and would cover her doll collection to smother its power. <PERSON> Toussaint </PERSON> told friends <PERSON> Rubia </PERSON> was slowly poisoning him, said Detective <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jose </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s missing-persons unit <PERSON> Rubia </PERSON> attended a Catholic retreat shortly before her disappearance at which she decided to leave her lover and devote herself to her husband and family, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said.
