<SECOND>AM-VA Foreclosures,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders VA in Washington State To Refund Foreclosure Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to refund $ 3 million to $ 6 million to veterans in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state who lost their homes in foreclosures on VA-backed loans. The order, received Monday by attorneys in the class-action suit, also ordered the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> to erase at least $ 45 million in debt the agency has tried to collect from more than 3,500 veterans who lost their homes to foreclosures. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> found the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> had violated a state law governing the amount of money that could be collected under a section providing a `` shortcut'' for foreclosures. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Leen </PERSON>, a lawyer representing five veterans, said a similar suit is pending in federal court in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and that more than $ 200 million in uncollected debts are at stake in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Several other states have laws similar to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s, which could mean hundreds of millions of dollars are due veterans who lost their homes, <PERSON> Leen </PERSON> said. Those states include <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON>, a law clerk to <PERSON> Leen </PERSON>. The Veterans Administration `` basically wanted their cake and they wanted to eat it too, plus a second helping,'' <PERSON> Leen </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state law established for lenders a shortcut way, known as non-judicial foreclosure, to seize a home from a borrower who failed to make payments on a home loan. In the five cases that made up the class-action suit, the VA chose the non-judicial route to save time and legal fees, believing it could rely on its own regulations to collect from veterans any extra costs it incurred, such as legal fees, court filing costs and losses on resale of the home. However, <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state law provided that lenders could not collect such extra money from debtors when the foreclosure was settled non-judicially, or out of court. <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>'s ruling said the law was meant to protect debtors and that it superceded the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s regulations. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON>, staff attorney for the VA in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said Tuesday the agency had not decided whether to appeal <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>'s ruling Part of that decision depends on what effect an appeal might have on other states, he said. <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>'s ruling requires the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> to repay veterans money collected in foreclosures since 1981, the effective date for the statute of limitations. <PERSON> Leen </PERSON> sued in 1987. VA officials estimated they had collected, and would need to refund, $ 3 million to $ 6 million. Last August, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> said it was trying to collect more than $ 45 million from veterans involved in foreclosures in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. <PERSON> Leen </PERSON> said papers the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> filed in court now place that figure at $ 63 million. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> stopped trying to collect foreclosure costs in June 1987 after <PERSON> Leen </PERSON> filed the class-action suit. The agency said the moratorium would last until the suit was settled. <PERSON> Leen </PERSON> filed the class-action lawsuit after winning a similar case for <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vallejo </PERSON>, 31, of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vallejo </LOCATION>, a roofer, sued the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> over $ 8,700 in foreclosure costs it sought from him after he lost his home in 1982. `` This is great,'' <LOCATION> Vallejo </LOCATION> said. `` A lot of people are going to get their money back.''
