<HEAD>Minority Station Owners More Likely To Aim Programs at Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Minority-owned broadcast stations provide more programming of interest to minorities than non-minority-owned stations, according to a congressional report. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> also found that stations owned by women cater to female audiences to a larger extent than male-owned stations, though not to the degree that minority-owned stations program to minority audiences. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications subcommittee, requested the study for use in a pending federal court case challenging the constitutionality of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s policy giving preference to minorities and women in awarding broadcast licenses The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had argued in that case, involving a new FM station at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Simon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, that its preference policy may be unconstitutional because it had no factual evidence that the policies contributed to diversity of programming at radio and television stations. However, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year added a stipulation to the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s budget authorization barring the agency from eliminating the preferences In releasing the study this week, <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said, `` The commission wanted empirical evidence, and now it has a clear record.'' <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Killory </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> general counsel, said the agency was reviewing the study and had no comment on it. `` The commission has to decide what position to take,'' she said. The study analyzed data from an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> survey of 8,720 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> radio and television stations, about 79 percent of the total. It cautioned about difficulty in determining to what extent a station's programming decisions was driven by the racial, ethinic or female make-up of its audience or resulted from minority-ownership interests. However, the report concluded, `` there is a strong indication that minority and women station-ownership results in a greater degree of minority programming.''
