<HEAD>Pentagon Chief Says He Will `Move Decisively'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said Tuesday he will `` move decisively'' and quickly against defense contractors implicated in the ongoing bribery investigation as soon as he receives more details from the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has already ordered a number of changes in the way the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> buys weapons and more are likely as a result of the investigation, he told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> probe centers on allegations that defense contractors and consultants, many of whom are former <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> employes, bribed <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials for inside details about contracts. No charges have yet been filed. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he had no new details about the two-year-old investigation, which became public June 14 when subpoenas were served around the nation. At one point, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> ordered contacts frozen on nine military programs because of the possibility that they may have been tainted, but he rescinded that order 10 days later when a quick review showed there were no problems. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> acted after an affidavit for a search warrant was unsealed in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, providing details about the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has sought to have the affidavits sealed, but several news organizations have challenged that action. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> promised to `` move decisively ... as soon as we receive facts from the Justice investigation.'' Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the committee, noted that `` in the next few weeks, it is expected that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> attorney will authorize the release of information on the investigation now under court seal. `` When that information is available, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> will have more specifics on contracts or source selections that may have been influenced by improper activities,'' he noted. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> repeated his appeals to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to wait until all the facts are made public before ordering sweeping overhauls in the complicated Pentagon purchasing procedures. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he meets daily with a special task force he set up last month to track the investigation and recommend changes. `` My instructions do not limit the nature of the changes,'' he said. `` Nothing is sacred _ neither organizational structure, regulations, nor the need to change existing law.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> cast cold water on one proposal which has surfaced in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ holding corporate chief executives responsible for their firms' actions. `` I think it's really impractical,'' he said, and would probably only result in firms declining to bid for Pentagon contracts. `` Ill-conceived reforms can quickly convince many firms that defense business does not provide a sufficient chance for a reasonable profit to make it worthwhile or compensate for the perennial ` stops and starts' of military business,'' he said. He said profit-and-earning `` ratios in the industry are alrady low. If we drive them down further, industry will lack the capital to keep up with modernization.'' He also warned against wide-ranging bans that attempt to close the so-called `` revolving door'' between government and private employment, such as working for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and then going to work for a defense contractor. `` The problems we face in attracting into government service talented individuals from the private sector would be exacerbated by the imposition of a broad post-government employment bar,'' he said.
