<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Drugs     07-26 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Drugs,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Reports Drug, Alcohol Abuse Declines In Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug and alcohol abuse in the armed forces is steadily declining from the alarmingly high levels of 1980, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said Tuesday. `` We are pleased with this latest decline, which can be attributed to the message that has been sent out to all our military personnel: If you want to stay in, you have to stay off drugs,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. The percentage of military personnel acknowledgng the use of illicit drugs in the 30 days prior to their being surveyed dropped from 27 percent in 1980, to 19 percent in 1982, 9 percent in 1985 and 5.5 percent in 1988. Alarm bells rang when the results of the first drug survey were released by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> in 1980. Comprehensive anonymous surveys have been conducted in 1980, 1982, 1985 and this year. In the latest survey, conducted for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the 17,213 men and women taking part did not put their names on the forms, and the exercise was not intended to root out abusers. Those answering the questionaires were chosen to provide a representative sampling of those in the armed forces by age, sex, ethnic group, rank and branch of service. Military officials also conduct random urine tests of suspected drug abusers, and those results also show a declining rate of use, officials say. The most common illegal drug was marijuana, used by 3 percent within the previous 30 days, down from 7 percent in 1985, and by 7 percent within the previous 12 months, down from 11 percent in 1985. Marijuana use was highest in the lower enlisted ranks, with 6 percent reporting use within the previous 30 days compared to 11 percent in 1985 and 15 percent within the previous 12 months, compared to 19 percent in 1985. Drinking also fell in the military, according to the survey. Heavy drinking, defined as consumption of five or more drinks at least once a week, was reported by 9 percent, down from 12 percent in 1985. And cigarette smoking was down to 57 percent who reported no puffing in the previous 30 days, compared to 54 percent in 1985. Twenty-three percent smoked a pack a day or more, compared to 27 percent in 1985. The final report, with a more complete breakdown of drug, alcohol and tobacco use, was to be complete in December, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said.
</TEXT>
