<HEAD>Reagan Orders Flags Lowered on 35th Anniversary of Korean War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met with a group of veterans of the Korean War on Tuesday and ordered flags flown at half staff on Wednesday in remembrance of the cease-fire that ended the conflict 35 years ago. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met with members of the Korean War Veterans Memorial Advisory Board and others. Retired Army Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stilwell </PERSON> is chairman of the board. He also issued a proclamation declaring the current week as National Week of Recognition and Remembrance for Those Who Served in the Korean War. He ordered the flags flown at half staff `` as a symbol of our gratitude to those who died as a result of their service in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and of our steadfast commitment to preserving the values for which they fought.'' `` As we approach the 35th anniversary of the cease-fire that marked the end of active combat in the Korean War, it is appropriate that we take time to remember and express our gratitude to those who served in that fierce conflict,'' the president said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s actions were requested in a resolution passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Congress two years ago approved construction of a Korean War Veterans Memorial, to be located on the Mall southeast of the Lincoln Memorial. Construction is likely to be completed early in the next decade.
