<HEAD>Four Opposition Parties Unite to Challenge Gandhi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four Indian opposition parties announced Tuesday they will merge to challenge Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> The announcement was made by V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a former defense minister and leader of the <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Morcha </PERSON>, or the People's Forum. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said the new party `` would spare no efforts ... to fulfill the aspirations of the people of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, who are today groaning under the corrupt and authoritarian rule of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> ally turned foe, defeated the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate for a seat in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in a June by-election in <LOCATION> Uttar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION> state. The united opposition party, to be called the <ORGANIZATION> Samajvadi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dal </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, will be formed by Aug. 15, <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said. The decision came after meetings with leaders from <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s party, the <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Lok </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dal </ORGANIZATION> and the Congress-S Party The Congress-S is a splinter group of <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s party. `` The merger will shake these gentlemen a bit _ these <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wallahs,'' said veteran opposition leader <PERSON> Biju </PERSON> <PERSON> Patnaik </PERSON>. `` Wallah'' is Hindi for man. The new party is expected to field candidates in parliamentary elections to take place before January 1990. Major opposition parties merged into the <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to defeat the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in general elections in 1977, but the government served only two years of its five-year term. The Parliament dissolved in 1979 after the coalition split and bickered over the choice for prime minister. <PERSON> Patnaik </PERSON> said the leadership of the new party has not been decided. The four parties control only two of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 25 state assemblies _ northern <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Karnataka </LOCATION> _ and their members hold just 21 seats in the 544-member law-making lower house of Parliament. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> holds more than 400 seats in the lower house, but its fortunes have been declining since it swept to victory in the 1984 general elections. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has lost 10 of 14 state elections held since then. It also lost four of the seven <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> seats in the by-elections. Much of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s decline has been blamed on allegations of inefficiency and corruption in government. News media and opposition politicans have alleged that kickbacks were paid on major defense contracts and that some money may have gone to <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> allies. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has denied that.
