<HEAD>Thunderstorms Scatter Rain, Some Hail over Central, Eastern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Thunderstorms scattered rain and hail over much of the central and eastern portions of the country Tuesday, but rainfall amounts were mostly moderate. In the South, showers and thunderstorms covered northern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, southeastern <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and northwestern <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, as well as northwestern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, received just under three-quarters of an inch of rain in six hours. Thunderstorms also stretched from the lower Great Lakes to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and down across the central Appalachians. Hail up to one inch in diameter pelted <LOCATION> Wernersville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, while <LOCATION> Elmira </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, recorded 0.88 inch of rain in the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT. Rain diminished in the central Plains during the morning, but thunderstorms were scattered over southern <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and northeast <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> in the afternoon. Thunderstorms in northeastern <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> dropped half-inch hail and heavy rain on <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION>, and storms also were reported in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures around the nation ranged from 62 degrees at <LOCATION> Crescent </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bend </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, to 108 degrees at <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The nation's overnight low was 42 degrees at <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thundersto