<HEAD>Inmate Sentenced In Stabbing With Steak Bone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUTLER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prison inmate was sentenced to 10 years in prison for stabbing another prisoner with a steak bone, and as a result of the attack inmates in solitary confinement do n't eat T-bone steaks any more A Union County jury Monday convicted <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> of aggravated assault and possession of contraband in the Nov. 11, 1987, stabbing of <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Raiford </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> was sentenced to 10 years for each conviction. The sentences will be served concurrently. <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> was stabbed with the sharpened bone from a T-bone steak that had been served the previous night to <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> and other inmates in solitary confinement, according to court testimony. <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> was stabbed in his back and leg and was treated at a hospital. Sgt. M.S. <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON>, who witnessed the attack, testified in the trial that T-bone steaks should not have been served to inmates confined for disciplinary reasons. `` It was an oversight, passing this kind of bone on to confinement inmates,'' he said. As a result of the attack, the Corrections Department implemented a new policy that prohibits T-bone steaks and pork chops with bones from being served to inmates in solitary confinement, said <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Tully </PERSON>, a department spokeswoman. Food service policy did not previously specify cuts of meat that should not be served. Steaks are served to inmates once every six weeks, she said. <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> claimed he stabbed <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> in self defense after the inmate threatened him and swung a razor blade at him in an exercise area. <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> said he found the bone on the ground as <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> approached. He is currently serving a 15-year sentence for trafficking in cocaine. According to <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> records, <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> entered prison on Dec. 31, 1986. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Roney </PERSON>, a deputy court clerk in <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON> will not begin serving the new sentences until he completes his current term.
