<TEXT>
 Elections to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> will take place June 15 and 18 next year, <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comunity </ORGANIZATION> ministers decided Tuesday after consulting with parliamentarians, it was officially reported. The vote will take place on Thursday June 15 in countries where elections are held on a weekday _ <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> _ and on Sunday June 18 in the eight other <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> member states _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>. This will be the third time that the 518-member European parliamentary assembly, which sits in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, will be directly elected. Its first direct election took place in 1979. It is held every five years.
