<FIRST>r a AM-TumorTreatment     07-26 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tumor Treatment,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Fights Brain Cancer With Innovative Treatment</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AH1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A teen-ager fighting the most malignant type of brain tumor is being treated with a relatively new technique that involves inserting tubes and radioactive beads into his head. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 18, was a week away from graduating from <ORGANIZATION> Wolbach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> this spring when he suffered a seizure. Doctors found he had a brain tumor just under 2 inches in diameter. Dr. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shewe </PERSON>, a radiation oncologist at <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Clarkson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, said standard therapy for the fast-growing tumor is surgery followed by radiation and chemotherapy, but the average patient survives only 40 to 50 weeks. About 20 percent of patients live two years; none has survived five. The new procedure combines surgery, chemotherapy and external and internal radiation, and doctors hope it will increase <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s survival rate. Preliminary tests on the newer treatment indicated the median survival time for patients has been extended to 87 weeks, <PERSON> Shewe </PERSON> said. The treatment is a five-step process, <PERSON> Shewe </PERSON> said. The first involves completing in three weeks rather than six the external radiation given before surgery. The compact treatment time may increase the effectiveness, <PERSON> Shewe </PERSON> said. The second step, chemotherapy, takes place concurrently, the doctor said. Step three is surgery to remove the tumor. Step four for <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> began when tiny radioactive beads were inserted through his scalp and into the center and around the tumor site to attack any remaining tumor cells, doctors said. The procedure utilizes sophisticated imaging equipment that shows cross-sections of the brain and a computer that helps plot the precise location of the tumor site. Neurosurgeon <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> drilled seven tiny holes in the skull and inserted seven tubes, or catheters, each less than a tenth of an inch in diameter. Each of the tubes was glued to a tiny button sewn to the scalp to hold it in place. A brain scan ensured the catheters were correctly positioned, and <PERSON> Shewe </PERSON> then inserted the radioactive beads. The radioactive materials remain at the tumor site for 96 hours before being removed. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> is scheduled to go home this week. He'll return for chemotherapy once every six weeks for a year, the fifth step in the therapy. Use of the implant began in 1977. In 1980, doctors first used the insertable catheter tubes with removable caps. And in 1983, at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, doctors began to use the implants to treat patients with so-called `` high-grade tumors.''
