<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman whose legs were crushed when a construction crane collapsed on her and whose bravery during the rescue won the nation's admiration will collect nearly $ 10 million for the injuries she suffered. <PERSON> Brigitte </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerney </PERSON> will receive $ 1 million immediately, $ 27,625 a month for a year, then the same monthly payment for the rest of her life with a compounded 3 percent increase each year, it was announced Tuesday. Mrs. <PERSON> Gerney </PERSON>, 52, was injured in May 1985 when a 35-ton crane, operated by an unlicensed worker, fell on her legs as she passed a site where a 42-story apartment house was being built. She told of the pain she went through when she testified at the trial of <PERSON> Lino </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmieri </PERSON>, the site foreman, and <ORGANIZATION> Crimmins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the company <PERSON> Palmieri </PERSON> worked for. `` I heard all the bones cracking,'' she said. `` I screamed for help. ` Help me! Help me! Get me out!''' She said she lay beneath the crane for six hours, in agony and with her legs crushed, while Detective <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ragonese </PERSON> pleaded with her to hang on to life. The payment, which settles a lawsuit filed by Mrs. <PERSON> Gerney </PERSON> against <PERSON> Crimmins </PERSON> and a number of other defendants, was reached after a session Monday in the courtroom of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trial judge, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Saxe </PERSON>. The judge offered guidance to the participants but did not hold a formal hearing. The money is to be paid to Mrs. <PERSON> Gerney </PERSON> through an annuity the defendants are setting up with an insurance company. The defendants in the lawsuit include the city, <PERSON> Crimmins </PERSON>, and several other construction-related companies. The suit was filed shortly after the criminal case ended in spring 1986. <PERSON> Palmieri </PERSON>, 54, was fined $ 5,000, put on five years' probation and ordered to perform community service for allowing an unqualified person, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricciardi </PERSON>, to operate the crane. Crimmins Construction was fined $ 10,000. <PERSON> Ricciardi </PERSON>, 31, pleaded guilty to second-degree assault, was sentenced to a few months in jail and was placed on probation. Mrs. <PERSON> Gerney </PERSON> underwent at least seven operations on her legs. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called her during her recovery and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> visited. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> threw a party for her. The settlement said that in the event of Mrs. <PERSON> Gerney </PERSON>'s death, her estate will receive the money for a minimum of 20 years. The total for a 20-year period would be $ 9,906,738. Her life expectancy is 29 years, said her lawyer, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Conason </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gerney </PERSON> could not be reached for comment and <PERSON> Conason </PERSON> would not disclose her whereabouts. `` She's a very private person,'' he said. `` She instructed us to say nothing.''
