e cease-fire would be monitored and supervised by about 250 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping troops. <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> television program `` This Morning'' that it would be possible to work out a cease-fire between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the next two months. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> budget crisis will make it hard, perhaps impossible to finance the peacekeeping force, unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other debtors pay their arrears. Such a force could cost $ 20 million to $ 30 million a year, according to early estimates. <PERSON> Francoic </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, spokesman for the secretary-general, told reporters Tuesday the organization is expected to run out of operating funds at the end of October. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has been withholding full dues payments to demand <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spending reforms.
