<HEAD>North Korea Again Demands It Co-Host Olympic Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, in a letter released Tuesday, said it would consider participating in the Olympic Games in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> but repeated its demand to be a co-host of the event that begins in September. The letter, which came as a suprise to South Korean leaders, linked negotiations on the Olympics with an earlier <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> proposal that the two countries hold parliamentary talks on a non-aggression pact. It said in part, `` We propose with courtesy that the scheduled North-South joint parliamentary conference be held within August at the latest before the opening of the Olympics and discuss as an urgent agenda such issues as your request for our participation in the Olympics and our proposal for its co-hosting.'' There was no immediate comment from the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government, which has not yet responded to the earlier North Korean letter calling for parliamentary talks. The peninsula was divided into communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and capitalist <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 1945 at the end of World War II. They fought a war in 1950-53 and remain enemies. The Olympic Games are to be held Sept. 17-Oct. 2 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> When <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s demand that it be a co-host of the games was rejected it announced a boycott. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> have said some events could be held in the <PERSON> North </PERSON>, but that the Games are awarded to a single host city and not to countries. The committee has said <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> could stage archery, table tennis, women's volleyball, preliminary 