rrect attitude, an ignorant attitude.'' `` We will never forget where we are located, and it is n't in the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, but in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> he said. `` Not 90 miles from <LOCATION> Odessa </LOCATION>, but 90 miles from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>.'' In the past two years, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has abandoned economic incentives aimed at boosting production and implemented a campaign of `` moral persuasion'' that emphasizes greater worker discipline. `` It would be totally incorrect for us to copy mechanically the solutions of other countries,'' <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> said, and what may be best for the Soviet bloc may not work for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Noting that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> achieved its status as one of the world's most powerful nations economically with an average of six vacation days per worker each year, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> called on Cubans to achieve more during the working hours they have. He said he was n't suggesting taking away vacations or increasing work schedules in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Two years ago, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> declared that worker absenteeism and inefficient production threatened to make <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> a nation of freeloaders. The Cuban leader cited a lengthy list of recent industrial and public works projects in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s second-largest city with a population of 962,000. Earlier Tuesday, Cubans marked the revolution's 35th anniversary by staging a symbolic attack on a military barracks that now is an elementary school. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> attended a ceremony in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> at 5 a.m., the exact time his revolution began, and watched youth groups mount a mock assault on the <PERSON> Moncada </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> in this eastern Cuban city. Although the 1953 attack failed, the brutality with which it was suppressed sparked popular support for <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s fight to overthrow rightist dictator <PERSON> Fulgencio </PERSON> <PERSON> Bastista </PERSON>. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> was imprisoned and later released. He fled the island, but returned with revolutionary forces aboard the yacht <ORGANIZATION> Granma </ORGANIZATION> in 1956 to start his guerrilla war in the mountains. The struggle ended in a triumphant march into <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> on Jan. 1, 1959, to begin Communist rule.
