<DATELINE>SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Army commanders testified Tuesday that they urged a private to abstain from sexual activity after he tested positive for the AIDS virus, but they never ordered him to abstain or warned him that his sexual conduct could be a crime. The commanders testified for the prosecution at the opening of the court-martial of Pvt. <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who in March 1987 became the first member of the military to be charged with AIDS-related offenses. Others to testify included a soldier identified only as <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>, and Spec. 4 <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pruitt </PERSON>, who was engaged to <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> for a time. Both women said <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> told them prior to having sex that he had a rare, incurable blood disease but did not mention AIDS. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> Caseyville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, is accused of having threatened the health of the two women and a third male soldier by failing to use condoms during sex and by failing to warn them he had tested positive for exposure to the AIDS virus. Col. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, a physician who commanded the hospital at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huachuca </LOCATION> in this southeast <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> town, said he counseled <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> in July 1986 after <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> tested positive to having antibodies to the human immunodeficiency virus -LRB- HIV -RRB-, which causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Presence of the antibodies indicates the person has been exposed to the virus, may develop AIDS and can spread it. <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> said he advised <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> to use condoms if he had sex and to avoid high-risk partners. But he said there was no order for those testing positive to abstain from sex nor any criminal sanction for sexual activity. Capt. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kulifay </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said he counseled <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> `` strictly man-to-man'' on several occasions between July 1986 and March 1987 and advised him that `` he should not screw around.'' <PERSON> Kulifay </PERSON> said his soldiers, including <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, watched a film in 1986 detailing AIDS and its transmission. But under cross-examination, <PERSON> Kulifay </PERSON> acknowledged that the film did not say that soldiers who tested positive for the virus but failed to abstain from sex were committing criminal conduct. Both <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kulifay </PERSON> said they never told <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> his sexual activity might be criminal. Late in the afternoon, the soldier identified only as Ms. <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> testified that she had sex twice with <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> in August 1986, the second time the night before her husband of one month arrived in <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vista </LOCATION>. She said <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> had told her `` that he had a rare blood disease and he could die at any moment.'' She said <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said the disease was fatal but did not mention HIV or AIDS. She acknowledged under cross-examination that she was testifying in exchange for immunity from charges of adultery, which is a military crime. She also said Army medical officials have told her she no longer is at risk for contracting the disease. The woman testified after the judge, Col. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, reversed himself and allowed her to testify under a pseudonym, despite defense objections. The prosecution had claimed that identifying the woman could harm her mental health. Ms. <PERSON> Pruitt </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> told her in 1986 he had `` an incurable blood disease'' but did n't say until January 1987 that it was AIDS. She said they had sex weekly from April to October 1986, with <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> using a condom about one-fourth of the time. She said they resumed relations in Jaunary 1987, even though she knew <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' test results and that AIDS is `` an incurable, contagious, fatal disease.'' She said she understood the risk. The soldier also said she and her child _ born last year and allegedly fathered by <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> _ have tested negative for HIV. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> has pleaded innocent to three counts of aggravated assault, three counts of conduct bringing discredit upon the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and one count of sodomy. He faces up to 17 years in prison, dishonorable discharge and forfeiture of all pay and allowances if convicted. When he was charged, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> was the first member of the military to face AIDS-related charges. Other cases have been brought since. In April, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> adopted regulations requiring commanders to warn soldiers testing positive for the AIDS virus that they face discharge or prosecution if they do n't tell sex partners about their condition or use condoms. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> have adopted similar regulations.
