<HEAD>Dollar Up Slightly, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar, reflecting its recent strength overseas, gained slightly in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today while stock prices rebounded in slow trading. The dollar opened at 132.25 yen and rose to 132.60 before edging down to close at 132.15, up 0.35 yen from Monday's close. `` Although there is no energy in the market that could keep carrying the dollar higher, the dollar seems to be receiving enough support to keep itself above the 132-yen level, at least for the time being,'' a trader at the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which shed 117 points Monday, gained 120.23 points or 0.44 percent to close at 27,303.76 in thin trading. `` It appears the market is going to hold back until the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> GNP figures,'' said one dealer. Investors on the stock market were taking a wait-and-see attitude ahead of Wednesday's scheduled announcement in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of second-quarter figures for the gross national product, the total retail value of goods and services produced by the country's economy in a given period `` If the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> GNP number is too strong, people are concerned about inflation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Hisamichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sawa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
