<HEAD>London Stocks Up 9.5 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices rose Tuesday in thin trading as players awaited Wednesday's British trade report for June. Dealers said there was a lack of substantive news on which to trade following Monday's featureless session. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was 9.5 points, or 0.5 percent, higher at 1,848.0 at midday. Volume was an extremely light 177.5 million shares, compared with 169.1 million shares at the same time Monday. Without major corporate news to affect equities, players chose to focus their attention on Wednesday's scheduled release of British trade figures for June. Economists said they expect <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s current account deficit to have narrowed to about 800 million pounds, or $ 1.38 billion, in June from 1.2 billion pounds in May and the merchandise trade deficit to have narrowed to about 1.3 billion pounds from 1.7 billion pounds.
</TEXT>
