<HEAD>Prime Withdraws Mini-Supercomputer From Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is withdrawing its MXCL5 mini-supercomputer from the marketplace and taking a $ 5 million charge against its second-quarter earnings. The company also said Monday it is canceling a marketing agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Cydrome </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Milpitas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, which manufactured the computer. Prime attributed the withdrawal of the MXCL5 to slower growth in the mini-supercomputer field and aggressive pricing by the company's competitors. `` Because of the intensely competitive pricing environment, we determined that sales of this product would not contribute significantly to the overall profitability of Prime,'' Prime President <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> said in a prepared statement. <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> said Prime would continue to evaluate the special-purpose processor market, which Prime entered in January in an attempt to compete with field leaders <ORGANIZATION> Alliant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Acton </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Convex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Richardson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Company officials said the second-quarter earnings reduction would amount to about 10 cents a share. Analysts had forecast earnings of about 23 cents to 27 cents a share. Prime is to announce quarterly earnings Thursday. The base price for the standard MXCL5 system was $ 579,000, while a more fully configured model was price at $ 774,000. The Unix-based system was designed for sophisticated engineering and scientific number-crunching. Prime announced in May it was laying off about 700 employees because of job redundancies and attrition after a February merger with <ORGANIZATION> Computervision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The merger moved Prime to second in the computer-aided design and computer-aided manufacturing market behind <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The company reported first quarter net income of $ 14.5 million of revenues of $ 363.7 million, including <ORGANIZATION> Computervision </ORGANIZATION> operations.
