<HEAD>Western European Car Industry Is Booming, Alas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Western European car industry, the world's largest, is enjoying record sales as consumers from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> flock to showrooms eager to buy `` new wheels. While this is undoubtedly good news, some industry people, believe it or not, find it distinctly worrying. The reason is that the boom has attracted more competitors in what already is a fiercely competitive market. That has heightened fears that the field will become overcrowded, leaving the car makers vulnerable in a downturn, which could come as soon as next year. `` The market is booming,'' said <PERSON> Sanjay </PERSON> <PERSON> Dabysing </PERSON>, head of the automotive group at <ORGANIZATION> DRI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a private economic forecasting firm in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Sales, which have been buoyant in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> since the mid-1980s, are expected to grow to a record 12.5 million cars this year from 12.4 million in 1987, <ORGANIZATION> DRI </ORGANIZATION> said. In comparison, 11.3 million cars were sold in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and 3.3 million in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in the most recent year. `` It's a representation of the reasonably good economic growth in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in recent years,'' said <PERSON> Garel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhys </PERSON>, an automotive economist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardiff </ORGANIZATION>. The sales growth stems from strong consumer spending created by income growth, tax cuts and an increasing willingness among Europeans to take on debt, the experts said. In addition, more businesses are using company cars, they said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> have been experiencing particularly strong demand, while sales have been slowed somewhat in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> by a sluggish economy. Import restraints and the overall buoyancy of the market have encouraged Japanese manufacturers to build more plants in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The market also has attracted other Asian and Eastern European competitors, like the makers of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s inexpensive <LOCATION> Yugo </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers have stepped up their activity by buying up European luxury car makers. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has bought <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has bought <ORGANIZATION> Automobili </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lamborghini </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which already owns <ORGANIZATION> Aston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lagonda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, is rumored to be interested in <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. `` The market has become more competitive,'' <PERSON> Dabysing </PERSON> said. Most of the competition still comes from other Europeans. Unlike the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where the Big Three automakers control the market, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> has a large number of domestically based manufacturers. The top six auto makers and their market shares in 1987, according to <ORGANIZATION> DRI </ORGANIZATION>, were: <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, 14.9 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, 14.2 percent; the combination of <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Automobiles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citroen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, 12.2 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, 12 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Renault </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, 10.6 percent, and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, 10.6 percent. The biggest rivalry among the Europeans is between <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION>, both of which are trying to expand their markets across the continent in anticipation of the Common Market's elimination of most trade barriers in 1992. <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, makes 60 percent of its sales in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, but expects to face new threats at home once trade restrictions on imports are lifted across the European Economic Community. The Japanese, meanwhile, have already captured 11.4 percent of the European market, mostly through imports, <ORGANIZATION> DRI </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The Japanese are now moving on to the next stage as they have in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, trying to diffuse the controversy that their sales have created in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Rhys </PERSON> said. The pioneer, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, operates a plant in <LOCATION> Sunderland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and has already doubled its planned 1992 capacity to 200,000 cars. `` There is no doubt that manufacturers like <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- will follow this route. Where and when is difficult to answer, but they will be coming,'' <PERSON> Dabysing </PERSON> said, adding that the Japanese might also bring over cars it makes in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Indeed, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, vice president for business strategy for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brentwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, said that's `` the biggest worry we have.'' The Japanese companies, already the most productive car makers, will be able to cut costs further when they set up more operations in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which will save them considerable transportation costs. `` We will get an excess capacity situation again, which will increase the cost pressures on everybody and will increase the competitive pressures,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. The market could develop an excess capacity of 1 million cars, he estimated. The 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> has yet to decide whether it will restrict Japanese imports after 1992, when it becomes a barrier-free marketplace. The experts are expecting the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> to choose a voluntary quota on Japanese car sales, perhaps limiting them to 10 percent of the market. `` Some people argue that there are too many independent manufacturers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Rhys </PERSON> said. `` If the market turned off considerably in the future, the firms would find it difficult to make profits and the question would be, how do the firms survive? The companies have toughened up by striving to become more productive and to produce higher quality cars, in an effort to close those gaps with the Japanese leaders. Western European makers have also joined forces, either through mergers or through joint ventures to produce various components, and in one case, an entire car. <ORGANIZATION> Renault </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Volksagen </PERSON> are working together on an automatic gear box; <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Volvo </ORGANIZATION> A.B. and <ORGANIZATION> Renault </ORGANIZATION> are working on an engine; <ORGANIZATION> Rover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> developed a car together, the Rover 800 also called the <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> Legend. This has helped the Western European makers _ which do not enjoy the economies of scale the Americans have _ to become more profitable. Although the drop in the dollar has hurt luxury car makers who export to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dabysing </PERSON> said that in 1987, `` they -LRB- the major European car makers -RRB- made money on the operations level for the first time in a long, long time and 1988 is proving to be a good year, too.'' The cloud on the horizon is the setback the industry is expecting in 1989. The experts are forcasting sales of 11.5 million cars to 11.75 million cars, a decline of as much as 8 percent. But the competitors wo n't be put off, the experts said. `` It's entrepreneurship. Hope springs eternal in the human breast,'' <PERSON> Rhys </PERSON> said. `` Everybody feels they can make a lot of money. It's a very big market and they want to be in it and they want to be in it in a bigger way in the future.''
