<HEAD>German Automakers Try Incentives To Lure U.S. Buyers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-European Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DEDERICHS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Buffeted by a cheaper dollar and Japanese competition, European carmakers are hoping to hold on to their lucrative slice of the American market. Two of them are trying new incentives to keep Americans buying. At present, the Europeans have a 5.1 percent share of the American mmarket, compared to 18.6 percent for the Japanese. `` Fly to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION>,'' says a newspaper advertisement of the West German automaker. The company offers a single business-class seat or two coach-class seats to anybody who orders a Mercedes in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It is the first time <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> buyers have been offered a free trip to pick up the prestige autos at the factory in <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION>. `` We offer them a luncheon and, if they want, a factory tour,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, spokesman of <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Montvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. Since the beginning of the advertising campaign earlier this year, about 700 Americans have accepted the offer, <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> said. With factory deliveries, buyers save $ 3,500 for the lower-priced Mercedes to almost $ 10,000 for the luxury model, <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> added. After the buyer completes his European vacation, the company arranges to ship the car without charge to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dealer who handles customs arrangements and other paperwork. For <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> cars delivered new in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, prices range from $ 29,190 for the 190E model with manual transmission to $ 77,065 for the 560 <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>. Last year, 89,000 Mercedes were sold on the American market. In the first six months of 1988, sales were steady at 44,066. Porsche, the West German builder of sports cars, lost some business this year mostly because of the weak dollar. `` That made our cars more expensive and less affordable,'' said <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Mckinley </PERSON> from the company's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> headquarters in <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. Porsche sold 12,824 cars in the first six months of 1987, but sales declined to 8,807 in the same period of this year. The company is now trying to recapture some ground with an incentive program. The company's Trust-Tourist Delivery program offers discounts between 7 and 10 percent, depending on the model, for all models ordered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and picked up in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Prices range from $ 26,560 for the Porsche 924 to $ 69,380 for the Porsche 928. The company sees its main competition from Japanese cars and from its German rival. `` In the lower-priced cars it's the Japanese product. When it comes to the expensive models, we have to fight Mercedes,'' she said. The Italian auto giant <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION>, which sells <ORGANIZATION> Alfa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Romeos </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lancia </ORGANIZATION> cars on the American market, has similar fears. The company took its own <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> models off the market because of the Japanese competition in the small-car area. <PERSON> Gualberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramieri </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, expects that the new <ORGANIZATION> Alfa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Romeo </ORGANIZATION> 164 will capture some lost ground in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The price for the car on the American market has not been fixed yet, he added. In the first six months of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> sold 2,708 <ORGANIZATION> Alfa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA