<HEAD>Government Lifts Import Ban On Beef</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> announced Tuesday it was lifting a three-year-old ban on imports of foreign beef, but said it would maintain an import quota system that has been opposed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> <PERSON> Kun-hwan </PERSON> said imports for 1988 would be limited to 14,500 tons. <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> did not say how much beef would be imported after this year, but indicated imports would be limited in order to protect the local beef industry. The end to the import ban was designed to avoid trade friction with foreign countries while at the same time alleviating domestic beef shortages, <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been pressing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to drop the ban on beef imports to help correct <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s $ 10 billion trade imbalance with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is also pressing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to drop restrictions or bans on many other imports and opposes the beef quota system. There was no immediate reaction from local farmers who have strongly opposed imports of beef unless the government guaranteed a definite price support system before lifting the import ban. Many Korean farmers went bankrupt due to an excessive import of foreign beef cattle before the last ban was imposed in 1985. Farmers have staged demonstrations to demand retention of the import ban. As reported previously, <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> said the proposed tonnage would include 3,000 tons of high quality beef for use at tourist hotels to be imported from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Officials said high quality beef could start arriving next month. The remaining 11,500 tons of both high quality and ordinary quality beef would be for general public consumption with sales open to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and other bidders. <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> said imported beef will be stockpiled for sales in case domestic sales prices exceed designated levels to seek price stabilization.
