<HEAD>Reagan To Hear GOP Views On Plant Closing Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout. Moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican congressional leaders told President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> today to use his `` best instincts'' in considering whether to veto the plant - closing bill One key <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senator predicted the legislation will become law no matter what the president does. House Republican leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> told reporters that `` arguments were made on both sides of the issue'' in a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> leaders with the president at the White House. `` Some of us in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> made the point that we were within the range of being able to sustain the president's veto if there were some work done and there was n't a diminution of votes on the Democratic side,'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> said `` There were arguments made on the other side too that frankly it was probably impossible to sustain in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and that maybe the president would want to give consideration to simply letting it become law,'' he said. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> said the president `` did not give an expression one way or another at all'' as to his intentions. The president told reporters at the opening of the meeting that he never decides about a bill until it reaches his desk. When asked what he believed the president would do, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> said, `` He's a very pragmatic individual and has been over eight years of time. I think the last word that was said was, ` Mr. President, just use your best instincts.'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> said that `` arguments were made with respect to how it may or may not affect the campaign,'' but Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ind </LOCATION>., said, `` I do n't think it will make much difference. `` My guess is plant closing will become law but the parts about layoffs will be very controversial and will lead to some litigation later on,'' he said. `` I think probably the vote is there in both houses to override. <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> said the Republicans in the meeting `` were expressing pretty good vote counts but saying the president ought to do his thing.'' The bill requires companies to give workers 60 days' notice of plant closings and layoffs. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Monday that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is likely to go ahead and veto the bill. But the spokesman also said no final decision had been made. `` It's always open until it's done,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters after the arrived at the White House for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s signature. The legislation passed both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by veto-proof margins, and some Republicans have said they're reluctant to vote against it because of polls showing broad public support for the proposal. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> disputed assertions that Republicans may be preparing to deliver that sort of message to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, saying, `` I would say there are number of them who will recommend a veto.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has until Aug. 3 to make a decision. He could veto the bill, sign it, or let it pass automatically into law without his signature. The administration's stand on the issue has been repeatedly assailed by Democrats, who say common decency requires that workers be told when they are about to lose their jobs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says business should have the `` flexibility'' to close plants and lay off workers without the 60 days' notice. Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, certain to get the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nomination for president in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> next month, has stated sentiments similar to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s on the issue, although there have been reports the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign would prefer to see the president let the bill become law to ease the political heat on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.
