 <ORGANIZATION> Transamerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reported earnings from continuing operations rose 7 percent in the second quarter, partly boosted by the acquisition of a commercial lending operation. Profits from continuing operations totaled $ 87.6 million, or $ 1.12 per share, up from $ 82.1 million, or $ 1.05 per share, in the second quarter of 1987. Consolidated net income, however, fell to $ 89.45 million from $ 105.96 million in the year-ago quarter. The financial services concern posted a $ 1.87 million after-tax gain from investment transactions in the second quarter. That's down from a similar gain of $ 8.26 million and $ 15.6 million in gains from discontinued operations posted in 1987. Revenue for the quarter totaled $ 1.996 billion, up from $ 1.977 billion for the same period in 1987. The insurance and financial services giant said expansion of its commercial lending and leasing operations contributed to the quarter and six-month earnings gains. `` Our insurance and finance operations both achieved outstanding results, reflecting the fundamental strength and earning power of our businesses,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer. Profits from continuing operations during the first half of 1988 were $ 163.1 million, or $ 2.08 per share, up 9 percent from 1987's $ 149.9 million, or $ 1.91 per share First half consolidated net income for 1988 totaled $ 166 million, including $ 3 million in other gains, while first-half 1987 consolidated net income of $ 217 million included $ 33 million of other gains and $ 34 million in income from discontinued oprations, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olsen </PERSON>, vice president of corporate relations. Total revenues for the first six months of 1988 were $ 3.975 billion, up from $ 3.810 billion for the same period last year, the company said. The company expanded its commercial lending operation with the acquisition in October 1987 of the <ORGANIZATION> Borg-Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acceptance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, now called <ORGANIZATION> Transamerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. In its life insurance operation, profits were increased by reducing expenses and higher yields on invested assets, the company said. Property and casualty insurance increases were attributed to expansions in workers' compensation and re-insurance production.
