<HEAD>Texaco, Chevron, Phillips Report Higher Profit; Amerada Hess Posts
Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Three of the nation's major oil companies, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Phillips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, on Tuesday said their profit for the second quarter was boosted by strength in refining, marketing and chemicals operations. <ORGANIZATION> Amerada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the 15th largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil company, reported a net loss of $ 23.5 million, compared with a year-earlier profit of $ 89.4 million, or $ 1.06 a share. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's third biggest oil company, said its second-quarter net income quadrupled, lifted by refining, marketing and chemicals as well as the sale of its West German subsidiary. The oil giant earned $ 527 million, or $ 2.17 a share, up from $ 129 million, or 53 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1987. Second-quarter revenue rose 10.6 percent, to $ 9.4 billion from $ 8.5 billion a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, emerged on April 7 from bankruptcy protection under Chapter 11 of the federal code. The company paid $ 3 billion to settle litigation with <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and initiated another $ 2.6 billion in payments to its other creditors. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings for the latest quarter include an after-tax gain of $ 301 million, or $ 1.24 a share, from the sale of its West German subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A.G </ORGANIZATION>. The sale was part of the company's restructuring program under the Chapter 11 proceedings. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> also signed a letter of intent in June to form a joint venture with Saudi investors to refine and market oil products in parts of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In the first half of the year, net income tripled to $ 769 million, or $ 3.17 a share, from $ 247 million, or $ 1.02 a share, in the same period in 1987. First-half revenue was up 6.5 percent, to $ 18.1 billion from $ 17.0 billion. Fourth-ranked <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said its second-quarter profit jumped 45 percent _ to $ 520 million, or $ 1.52 a share, from $ 358 million, or $ 1.04 a share, a year earlier. Second-quarter revenue was unchanged from a year earlier, at $ 7.3 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Keller </PERSON> said the company's profit margins from sales of oil products were the highest in two years, while chemical operations continued to benefit from strong demand in the industrial market. Earnings in the first six months increased 63 percent _ to $ 1.2 billion, or $ 3.43 a share, from $ 719 million, or $ 2.10 a share. Revenue for the period edged up 5 percent, to $ 14.8 billion from $ 14.1 billion. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, the nation's eighth biggest oil company, saw its earnings in the quarter soar to $ 170 million, or 72 cents a share, from $ 3 million a year earlier. The <LOCATION> Bartlesville </LOCATION>, Okla.-based company said that although its gains were broad-based, refining and marketing were especially strong. First-half profit was $ 300 million, or $ 1.27 a share, compared with a loss of $ 29 million in January-June 1987. Revenue for the six months rose to $ 5.78 billion from $ 5.18 billion. New York-based <PERSON> Amerada </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said its second-quarter net loss of $ 23.5 million included a loss from refining and marketing operations of $ 6.5 million, compared with profit of $ 55.7 million a year earlier. Second-quarter revenue fell to $ 882.8 million from $ 1.1 billion a year earlier. In the first half, <PERSON> Amerada </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> earned $ 42.2 million, or 51 cents a share, down from $ 270.8 million, or $ 3.21 a share. Revenue for the period declined to $ 2.1 billion from $ 2.4 billion.
