 Representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday failed to resolve a labor dispute that could halt rail service for 40,000 Chicago-area commuters. Negotiations in the presence of federal mediators adjourned for the day without an accord, but a government official said he would not characterize the talks as unproductive. `` They're still talking,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. `` All I can really say is that mediation is in progress and, as far as we're concerned, it's going to go right down to the deadline ... We'll be available as long as we can help.'' While the two sides met behind closed doors at the board's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> offices, an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> congressman introduced legislation to push them closer to an agreement and block a threatened Aug. 4 strike C & amp; NW provides the principal daily rail service for about 40,000 commuters in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area. `` Although I dislike intervention by the federal government, we can not stand idly by,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>. `` Congress may act if they fail to do so. <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>'s bill would require the company and union to accept as binding the recommendations of a presidential emergency board appointed to examine the dispute if the two sides fail to reach agreement on their own by the strike deadline. At issue is a plan by <ORGAN