<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip As Doubts Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Renewed pessimism about <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to control its oil production has stalled the recent advance of oil futures prices. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, contracts for September delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate crude, the nation's benchmark grade, settled Monday at $ 16.05 per barrel, off 33 cents from Friday's close. The near-term crude contract gained $ 1.41 per barrel last week. Refined products also lost ground. The near-term contract for wholesale gasoline fell .85 cent per gallon to settle at 51.22 cents, and heating oil dropped .78 cent per gallon to finish at 44.17 cents. Traders said activity was light as market attitudes turned bearish about the cartel's chances for limiting overproduction and firming prices. The market's strong move last week stemmed from bullish interpretations of a proposed cease-fire between <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> combatants <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and reports that members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> would meet soon to discuss prices. Both were interpreted as signs that fractious elements in the gulf would be able to overcome their differences and prop up the sagging oil market. The respected <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s pricing committee would meet Aug. 3 in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, but the news failed to inspire traders to follow through on the market's previous gains Instead, traders said, the market appeared to recoil with its characteristic doubts about whether <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ever could get together on the price issue. `` After a runup based on speculation, there's a natural amount of profit taking,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Redoglio </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
