<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   07-26 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Domestic Car And Truck Sales Rise 5 Percent In Mid-July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Auto sales probably will continue at mid-July's uneventful rate or slower through August and until the end of the car model year, according to one industry analyst Combined <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of domestically built cars and light trucks rose 5 percent on a daily basis July 11-20 from the comparable period of 1987, to 349,263 from 295,755, automakers reported Monday. There were nine selling days in this year's period and eight last year. Sales moved at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 7.8 million, trailing rates that frequently topped 8 million in the first half of the year, but closer to the 7.7 million rate of mid-July 1987. Last August, dealers used buyer incentives to clear excess cars from their crowded lots. After a hot-selling first half of 1988, auto inventories are low, analyst <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Cedergren </PERSON> said Monday. `` This year they wo n't need the fire sale approach,'' said <PERSON> Cedergren </PERSON>, of J.D. <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Agoura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported increases in daily car sales from July 11-20, offsetting a slight decline in <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> car sales <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> sold 106,791 cars in the nine-day period, up from 96,746 in eight days of the comparable period last year. Daily sales were down 1.9 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold 69,039 cars, up from 55,686 a year earlier, a 10.2 percent increase in daily sales. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> sold 29,956 cars, up from 24,037, a 10.8 percent daily increase. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> sold 53,434 light trucks, up 7.7 percent on a daily sales basis, and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> sold 29,172, up 9.8 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold 45,426 light trucks, with the daily sales rate down 0.8 percent. `` It is an indication that finally sales are beginning to slow down to more of a normal pace. It's a slight slowdown in the marketplace, but still a pretty healthy rate,'' <PERSON> Cedergren </PERSON> said. Erratic sales last year exaggerate fluctuations among manufacturers from 10-day period to period, he said. `` It all depends who had incentive programs going last year and who has them this year.'' Overall, he said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, with 49 percent of the market in domestically made cars, has halted an erosion in its market share. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, with 31.7 percent, and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, with 13.7 percent, have shown slight gains, partly at the expense of imports facing price disadvantages because of changing exchange rates, <PERSON> Cedergren </PERSON> said. Sales of imported cars and trucks are reported at the end of each month. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> sold 6,344 of its U.S.-made cars in the mid-July period, up from 5,469, a 3.1 percent daily sales gain. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> had a 0.6 percent gain, selling 3,376 U.S.-made cars, up from 2,984 a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> sold 1,745 domestically produced autos, up from 874 in a period when its plant was n't fully operational a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> sold 690 U.S.-made cars. It did not begin domestic manufacturing until September 1987.
</TEXT>
